1
00:00:23,007 --> 00:00:24,873
["THE JAMES BOND THEME" PLAYING]

2
00:00:37,021 --> 00:00:38,353
[GUNSHOT]

3
00:00:53,170 --> 00:00:54,770
Q:       
               I've being saying
                for years, sir,

4
00:00:54,772 --> 00:00:56,838
that our special equipment
             is obsolete.

5
00:00:56,840 --> 00:00:58,907
And now,        
       computer analysis reveals

6
00:00:58,909 --> 00:01:00,542
an entirely new approach:

7
00:01:00,544 --> 00:01:01,609
Miniaturization.

8
00:01:01,611 --> 00:01:03,878
For instance, radioactive lint.

9
00:01:05,349 --> 00:01:07,599
When placed       
       in an opponent's pockets,

10
00:01:07,601 --> 00:01:10,069
the antipersonnel       
 and location fix seems obvious.

11
00:01:10,071 --> 00:01:14,106
What we want              
is a location fix on 007.

12
00:01:14,108 --> 00:01:17,443
Number 10 is making ugly noises 
    about Operation Bedlam.

13
00:01:17,445 --> 00:01:18,610
Ms. Moneypenny,

14
00:01:18,612 --> 00:01:20,312
<i> have you checked</i>             
<i> with Communications?</i>

15
00:01:20,314 --> 00:01:22,781
Replies to our Cairo, Amsterdam 
     and Madrid inquiries:

16
00:01:22,783 --> 00:01:24,032
all negative, sir.

17
00:01:24,034 --> 00:01:27,286
The PM wants to be informed     
personally when we find 007.

18
00:01:27,288 --> 00:01:28,553
[ENGINE REVS LOUDLY]

19
00:01:28,555 --> 00:01:30,355
[♪♪♪]

20
00:01:41,084 --> 00:01:42,450
[CAR HORN HONKING]

21
00:01:54,581 --> 00:01:55,714
Hm.

22
00:03:56,987 --> 00:03:58,003
WOMAN:             
             Don't.

23
00:04:01,992 --> 00:04:03,658
[WOMAN GASPING]

24
00:04:25,014 --> 00:04:26,147
[EXHALES HEAVILY]

25
00:04:32,589 --> 00:04:33,639
Good morning.

26
00:04:33,641 --> 00:04:36,858
My name's Bond.         
          James Bond.

27
00:04:36,860 --> 00:04:38,026
Miss, uh--?

28
00:04:38,028 --> 00:04:39,811
MAN:                            
Don't move, Mr. Bond.

29
00:04:44,318 --> 00:04:45,350
Now, get up.

30
00:04:46,653 --> 00:04:48,052
Put your hands         
       behind your head.

31
00:04:48,054 --> 00:04:49,037
Move.

32
00:04:49,039 --> 00:04:50,705
[WHIMPERING]

33
00:04:59,182 --> 00:05:00,282
Get in.

34
00:05:05,088 --> 00:05:06,254
Lie down.

35
00:05:10,344 --> 00:05:11,510
[GUNSHOT]

36
00:05:11,512 --> 00:05:12,827
[♪♪♪]

37
00:05:13,630 --> 00:05:14,863
[GUNSHOT]

38
00:05:34,417 --> 00:05:35,650
[WOMAN SCREAMS]

39
00:05:38,172 --> 00:05:39,171
[GASPS]

40
00:05:44,244 --> 00:05:45,844
[GRUNTING]

41
00:06:21,331 --> 00:06:22,347
[YELLS]

42
00:06:44,488 --> 00:06:45,503
[ENGINE REVS]

43
00:06:52,779 --> 00:06:55,012
This never happened   
          to the other fellow.

44
00:06:55,014 --> 00:06:58,216
[♪♪♪]

45
00:09:33,607 --> 00:09:34,606
[HORN HONKS]

46
00:09:39,880 --> 00:09:41,145
PORTER:                    
Your baggage, sir?

47
00:09:41,147 --> 00:09:43,048
BOND:                 
      In the boot.              
Take care of those clubs.

48
00:09:43,050 --> 00:09:44,032
Right, sir.

49
00:09:45,802 --> 00:09:47,168
[CONVERSING INDISTINCTLY]

50
00:09:48,205 --> 00:09:49,871
Commander Bond.                
How are you, sir?

51
00:09:49,873 --> 00:09:51,172
Fine.         
        Good to see you, Manuel.

52
00:09:51,174 --> 00:09:53,041
[SPEAKS IN PORTUGUESE]

53
00:09:53,043 --> 00:09:54,642
Everything seems up
               to the Palacio's

54
00:09:54,644 --> 00:09:55,743
usual high standards.

55
00:09:55,745 --> 00:09:57,611
Yes, it's a good season.

56
00:09:57,613 --> 00:09:59,180
By the way,      
        that red Cougar outside,

57
00:09:59,182 --> 00:10:00,347
does it belong to a lady?

58
00:10:00,349 --> 00:10:02,183
Yes, sir.              
Contessa Teresa di Vincenzo.

59
00:10:02,185 --> 00:10:03,768
<i> Que bella.</i>

60
00:10:05,772 --> 00:10:07,438
Our best.

61
00:10:07,440 --> 00:10:09,974
Fortunately,       
     we have had a cancellation.

62
00:10:11,411 --> 00:10:13,144
Allow me.

63
00:10:13,146 --> 00:10:15,246
[WOMEN LAUGHING FAINTLY OUTSIDE]

64
00:10:18,652 --> 00:10:20,652
[PEOPLE LAUGHING AND CHATTERING
           IN DISTANCE]

65
00:10:20,654 --> 00:10:22,419
Mm.

66
00:10:22,421 --> 00:10:24,873
This will do.          
    This will do me nicely.

67
00:10:24,875 --> 00:10:27,608
MANUEL:                         
I'm sure we can look after      
your special needs.

68
00:10:27,610 --> 00:10:29,978
BOND:      
               I'm sure you can.
                   Thank you.

69
00:10:31,614 --> 00:10:33,915
<i> [ROULETTE WHEEL SPINNING]</i>

70
00:10:34,951 --> 00:10:36,717
<i> [BALL FALLS IN SLOT]</i>

71
00:10:37,387 --> 00:10:39,453
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

72
00:10:57,024 --> 00:10:58,539
<i> Huit.</i>

73
00:10:58,541 --> 00:10:59,807
<i> À la pointe.</i>

74
00:11:03,346 --> 00:11:05,346
<i> Deux mille à la banque.</i>
             Give<i> la banque.</i>

75
00:11:05,348 --> 00:11:06,647
<i> Banco.</i>

76
00:11:06,649 --> 00:11:08,433
<i> Les jeux sont faits, monsieur.</i>
              <i> Change.</i>

77
00:11:15,441 --> 00:11:16,440
<i> Carte.</i>

78
00:11:17,427 --> 00:11:19,160
<i> Neuf. À la banque.</i>

79
00:11:21,831 --> 00:11:23,030
Thank you.

80
00:11:24,501 --> 00:11:26,800
<i> Quatre mille à la banque.</i>      
 Give<i> la banque.</i>

81
00:11:27,970 --> 00:11:30,070
WOMAN:<i> Avec.</i>                    
MAN 1:<i> Pointe gagnée.</i>

82
00:11:30,973 --> 00:11:32,273
<i> Suivi.</i>

83
00:11:38,381 --> 00:11:40,315
<i> Carte.</i>

84
00:11:40,317 --> 00:11:41,649
MAN 1: 
                        <i> Quatre.</i>

85
00:11:41,651 --> 00:11:43,118
[PEOPLE GASP]

86
00:11:43,120 --> 00:11:44,552
<i> Neuf. </i>

87
00:11:47,958 --> 00:11:49,290
<i> Vingt mille.</i>

88
00:11:49,292 --> 00:11:51,042
<i> La banque, vingt mille.</i>
             Give<i> la banque.</i>

89
00:11:51,044 --> 00:11:53,078
<i> Vingt mille à la banque.</i>    
         Give<i> la banque.</i>

90
00:11:53,080 --> 00:11:54,546
MAN 2:    
                    <i> La banque</i>  
                 <i> a vingt mille.</i>

91
00:11:54,548 --> 00:11:55,613
<i> Vingt mille,</i>
                    <i> la banque.</i>

92
00:11:55,615 --> 00:11:56,965
MAN 3:                          
Twenty thousand francs.

93
00:11:56,967 --> 00:11:58,917
MAN 2:         
       <i> La banque a vingt mille.</i>

94
00:11:58,919 --> 00:12:01,386
Too rich for my blood.

95
00:12:01,388 --> 00:12:03,988
MAN 2:             
    <i> Vingt mille, la banque.</i>    
     <i> Banque, vingt mille.</i>

96
00:12:03,990 --> 00:12:05,006
WOMAN:             
            <i> Banco.</i>

97
00:12:05,008 --> 00:12:06,341
MAN 1:    
                  <i> Banco debout.</i>

98
00:12:19,840 --> 00:12:20,822
<i> Carte.</i>

99
00:12:28,314 --> 00:12:29,430
MAN 1:
                          <i> Neuf.</i>

100
00:12:31,668 --> 00:12:33,201
[CROWD GROANS]

101
00:12:33,203 --> 00:12:35,053
<i> La banque a gagné.</i>

102
00:12:37,207 --> 00:12:38,339
Madame?

103
00:12:38,341 --> 00:12:40,508
[WHISPERS]           
    I don't have the money.

104
00:12:40,510 --> 00:12:43,711
<i> Je regrette, madame,</i> 
         <i> mais c'est impossible.</i>

105
00:12:43,713 --> 00:12:45,930
Mm. I regret too,               
but I don't have any money.

106
00:12:45,932 --> 00:12:46,914
[WHISPERS]

107
00:12:46,916 --> 00:12:48,266
Dame can't pay up.

108
00:12:48,268 --> 00:12:50,018
<i> S'il vous plaît, madame,</i>
            <i> venez avec moi.</i>

109
00:12:50,020 --> 00:12:51,619
<i> S'il vous plaît,</i>               
<i> madame...</i>

110
00:12:51,621 --> 00:12:53,954
Forgive me.     
          My mind was elsewhere.

111
00:12:53,956 --> 00:12:57,525
Madame has forgotten we agreed
   to be partners this evening.

112
00:12:57,527 --> 00:12:58,726
Please continue.

113
00:12:58,728 --> 00:13:00,328
MAN 2:             
            <i> Merci.</i>

114
00:13:00,330 --> 00:13:01,563
<i> Quarante mille</i>                 
<i> à la banque.</i>

115
00:13:01,565 --> 00:13:03,148
That's a bit of luck,

116
00:13:03,150 --> 00:13:05,517
being bailed out like that      
at the last minute.

117
00:13:10,240 --> 00:13:11,539
Waiter.

118
00:13:14,611 --> 00:13:15,759
Dom Perignon, '57.           
                 Sir.

119
00:13:21,200 --> 00:13:24,419
Why do you persist              
in rescuing me, Mr. Bond?

120
00:13:24,421 --> 00:13:26,337
It's becoming a habit,
             Contessa Teresa.

121
00:13:26,339 --> 00:13:29,406
Teresa was a saint.        
     I'm known as Tracy.

122
00:13:30,727 --> 00:13:33,761
Tracy, next time play it safe
         and stand on five.

123
00:13:33,763 --> 00:13:36,113
People who want to stay alive   
        play it safe.

124
00:13:37,250 --> 00:13:39,067
Please stay alive,

125
00:13:39,069 --> 00:13:40,234
at least for tonight.

126
00:13:45,609 --> 00:13:48,209
Come later.

127
00:13:48,211 --> 00:13:51,628
I hope it'll be worth it,    
            partner.

128
00:13:53,133 --> 00:13:54,465
<i> Monsieur?</i>

129
00:13:54,467 --> 00:13:56,868
Send it to suite 423  
          with caviar for two.

130
00:13:56,870 --> 00:13:58,836
<i> Oui, monsieur.</i>

131
00:14:21,861 --> 00:14:22,993
Tracy?

132
00:14:26,366 --> 00:14:27,381
Tracy?

133
00:14:34,074 --> 00:14:35,122
[GRUNTS]

134
00:14:35,876 --> 00:14:37,125
[GROANS]

135
00:14:44,551 --> 00:14:46,383
[GROANING]

136
00:15:22,038 --> 00:15:23,538
Gate-crasher.

137
00:15:24,474 --> 00:15:25,556
I'll leave you to tidy up.

138
00:15:39,171 --> 00:15:42,389
Mm. Royal beluga,  
           north of the Caspian.

139
00:16:00,476 --> 00:16:01,509
[SIGHS]

140
00:16:28,154 --> 00:16:31,122
You're full of surprises,
               contessa.

141
00:16:31,124 --> 00:16:32,205
So are you, Mr. Bond.

142
00:16:34,009 --> 00:16:36,110
Do you always arm yourself      
for a rendezvous?

143
00:16:36,112 --> 00:16:39,380
Occasionally.       
    I seem to be accident-prone.

144
00:16:39,382 --> 00:16:41,616
I'll take that,     
           if you don't mind.

145
00:16:41,618 --> 00:16:44,685
You're very sure of yourself,   
aren't you?

146
00:16:44,687 --> 00:16:46,421
Suppose I were to kill you      
for a thrill?

147
00:16:46,423 --> 00:16:49,039
I can think of something
          more sociable to do.

148
00:16:51,043 --> 00:16:54,345
Stop playing games.     
  Who was that man in your room?

149
00:16:54,347 --> 00:16:55,412
You're hurting me.

150
00:16:55,414 --> 00:16:56,914
I thought that was the idea
               tonight.

151
00:16:56,916 --> 00:16:58,115
Now, who was he?

152
00:16:58,117 --> 00:16:59,817
I don't know             
what you're talking about.

153
00:17:01,287 --> 00:17:03,054
I can be a lot more persuasive,
            contessa.

154
00:17:03,056 --> 00:17:05,056
I'm sure you can.

155
00:17:08,144 --> 00:17:09,143
Whatever else I may be,

156
00:17:09,145 --> 00:17:11,362
I'm not a liar.

157
00:17:11,364 --> 00:17:12,997
[♪♪♪]

158
00:17:14,034 --> 00:17:15,799
Get dressed.

159
00:17:25,745 --> 00:17:26,744
[GUN CLICKS]

160
00:17:39,559 --> 00:17:41,809
BOND:          
       You know, you're the most
          extraordinary girl.

161
00:17:41,811 --> 00:17:45,078
I'm not interested in    
   your opinion of me, Mr. Bond.

162
00:17:45,080 --> 00:17:47,247
I'm here for a business
               transaction.

163
00:17:47,249 --> 00:17:48,382
Really?

164
00:17:53,856 --> 00:17:56,757
Isn't Le Bleu          
     a bit heady for that?

165
00:17:56,759 --> 00:18:00,528
So you know your perfumes.
        What else do you know?

166
00:18:00,530 --> 00:18:02,763
A little about women.

167
00:18:02,765 --> 00:18:04,932
Think about me

168
00:18:04,934 --> 00:18:07,702
as a woman    
             you've just bought.

169
00:18:07,704 --> 00:18:09,537
Who needs to buy?

170
00:18:13,409 --> 00:18:15,976
Look, you don't owe me a thing.

171
00:18:18,881 --> 00:18:20,881
I think you're in some sort     
        of trouble.

172
00:18:20,883 --> 00:18:23,050
Would you like to talk about it?

173
00:18:23,052 --> 00:18:25,052
No, Mr. Bond.

174
00:18:25,054 --> 00:18:29,089
The only thing you need know  
about me is that I pay my debts.

175
00:18:30,560 --> 00:18:32,860
Twenty thousand francs          
is a lot of money.

176
00:18:34,664 --> 00:18:35,730
Mm.

177
00:18:42,372 --> 00:18:44,104
[WOMAN SQUEALS, LAUGHS]

178
00:18:44,106 --> 00:18:47,575
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

179
00:19:10,132 --> 00:19:11,799
WOMAN:            
  <i> Good morning, Commander Bond.</i>

180
00:19:11,801 --> 00:19:13,501
Good morning.<i> </i>         
     <i> Café complet</i> for two

181
00:19:13,503 --> 00:19:14,835
with fresh orange juice.

182
00:19:14,837 --> 00:19:15,836
<i> Yes, sir.</i>

183
00:19:15,838 --> 00:19:17,905
Connect me with suite 423,   
            please.

184
00:19:17,907 --> 00:19:20,641
<i> The Contessa di Vincenzo</i>    
   <i> has left the hotel, sir.</i>

185
00:19:20,643 --> 00:19:21,642
Checked out?

186
00:19:21,644 --> 00:19:23,110
<i> A few minutes ago.</i>

187
00:19:23,112 --> 00:19:24,277
Thank you.

188
00:19:35,542 --> 00:19:38,492
Paid in full, as well.

189
00:19:42,982 --> 00:19:44,382
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

190
00:19:44,384 --> 00:19:45,549
Thank you.

191
00:19:48,388 --> 00:19:50,187
Mr. Bond?   
      Yes.

192
00:19:50,189 --> 00:19:52,390
You've lost something.
      Really?

193
00:19:54,360 --> 00:19:55,860
[♪♪♪]

194
00:19:55,862 --> 00:19:57,744
We'll give it to you
                  outside.

195
00:19:59,816 --> 00:20:01,915
BOND:              
    Why not? Perhaps we can     
      make up a foursome.

196
00:20:04,654 --> 00:20:06,453
You've thought of everything.

197
00:20:07,723 --> 00:20:10,208
What a lovely surprise,     
   our meeting again so soon.

198
00:20:10,210 --> 00:20:11,242
[GRUNTS]

199
00:20:11,244 --> 00:20:12,443
BOND:              
           Thank you.

200
00:20:18,167 --> 00:20:20,100
And where's the party      
           this time?

201
00:20:20,102 --> 00:20:21,735
You have an appointment.

202
00:20:21,737 --> 00:20:23,704
Business or pleasure?

203
00:20:25,141 --> 00:20:27,108
Mystery tour, eh?

204
00:20:29,612 --> 00:20:31,545
I think we'd all enjoy it    
       more without that.

205
00:20:33,700 --> 00:20:35,065
[GRUNTS]

206
00:20:43,142 --> 00:20:44,575
[HORN HONKS]

207
00:21:08,150 --> 00:21:09,282
[WHISTLING]

208
00:21:26,119 --> 00:21:27,284
[GRUNTING]

209
00:21:37,797 --> 00:21:38,829
[LOCK CLICKS]

210
00:21:38,831 --> 00:21:40,298
[POUNDING ON DOOR]

211
00:21:40,300 --> 00:21:41,865
<i> Basta!</i>

212
00:21:41,867 --> 00:21:43,217
[POUNDING ON DOOR STOPS]

213
00:21:45,454 --> 00:21:46,837
Do not kill me, Mr. Bond.

214
00:21:46,839 --> 00:21:49,040
At least, not until
              we've had a drink.

215
00:21:49,042 --> 00:21:51,926
Then, if you wish,     
   I'll give you another chance.

216
00:21:51,928 --> 00:21:52,927
I'm Draco,

217
00:21:52,929 --> 00:21:54,261
of Draco Construction.

218
00:21:58,734 --> 00:21:59,733
Mm-hm.

219
00:22:06,875 --> 00:22:08,359
But today is the 13th,     
           commander.

220
00:22:08,361 --> 00:22:10,244
I'm superstitious.

221
00:22:10,246 --> 00:22:11,779
A martini for our guest, Olympe.

222
00:22:11,781 --> 00:22:12,780
OLYMPE:                         
A pleasure.

223
00:22:12,782 --> 00:22:14,949
Shaken, not stirred.

224
00:22:14,951 --> 00:22:16,750
Of course.                   
        Campari for me.

225
00:22:16,752 --> 00:22:17,751
Mm-hm.

226
00:22:19,021 --> 00:22:21,621
My apologies for the way  
    you were brought here today.

227
00:22:21,623 --> 00:22:22,957
Please sit down.

228
00:22:22,959 --> 00:22:26,309
I was not sure you would 
     accept a formal invitation.

229
00:22:26,311 --> 00:22:28,979
There's always something formal 
about the point of a pistol.

230
00:22:28,981 --> 00:22:31,147
[CHUCKLES]

231
00:22:31,149 --> 00:22:32,983
Thank you,<i> chéri.</i>

232
00:22:32,985 --> 00:22:35,318
Olympe, we will finish 
          our struggle later.

233
00:22:35,320 --> 00:22:36,353
As you wish.

234
00:22:37,607 --> 00:22:40,474
She also plays a very good   
         game of chess.

235
00:22:40,476 --> 00:22:41,475
<i> Salute.</i>

236
00:22:41,477 --> 00:22:42,977
Cheers.

237
00:22:44,146 --> 00:22:47,147
You usually drink               
Corsican brandy.

238
00:22:47,149 --> 00:22:48,899
Ah. What else do you know
               about me?

239
00:22:48,901 --> 00:22:51,369
Marc Ange Draco:          
  Head of the Union Corse.

240
00:22:51,371 --> 00:22:53,838
One of the biggest              
crime syndicates in Europe.

241
00:22:53,840 --> 00:22:55,506
The biggest.          
Not quite.

242
00:22:55,508 --> 00:22:58,793
An organization known as SPECTRE
operates worldwide.

243
00:22:58,795 --> 00:23:00,594
However, your legitimate        
business fronts

244
00:23:00,596 --> 00:23:01,862
are somewhat more extensive.

245
00:23:02,832 --> 00:23:05,166
Construction,                   
electrical supplies,

246
00:23:05,168 --> 00:23:08,035
numerous agricultural holdings.

247
00:23:08,037 --> 00:23:12,406
Your dossier on me...  
       is not entirely complete.

248
00:23:14,910 --> 00:23:18,045
I am also Teresa's father.

249
00:23:18,047 --> 00:23:20,413
Tracy.                   
                Yes, Tracy.

250
00:23:20,415 --> 00:23:23,533
Tracy. My only child.

251
00:23:25,170 --> 00:23:27,104
Her mother was an English girl.

252
00:23:27,106 --> 00:23:29,306
A romantic        
       who had come to Corsica

253
00:23:29,308 --> 00:23:31,709
to look for bandits.

254
00:23:31,711 --> 00:23:33,978
Rather like those women  
    who ventured into the desert

255
00:23:33,980 --> 00:23:35,345
looking for sheiks.

256
00:23:36,682 --> 00:23:39,116
She found me in the mountains

257
00:23:39,118 --> 00:23:41,585
hiding from the police  
             at the time.

258
00:23:41,587 --> 00:23:43,454
I came to love this girl.

259
00:23:43,456 --> 00:23:46,190
We married.    
             The result: Teresa.

260
00:23:47,960 --> 00:23:50,327
Twelve years later,
                my wife died.

261
00:23:50,329 --> 00:23:51,962
I sent Teresa to Switzerland...

262
00:23:51,964 --> 00:23:53,164
No, thanks,                     
I prefer my own.

263
00:23:53,166 --> 00:23:55,132
...to finish her education.

264
00:23:55,134 --> 00:23:58,201
Unfortunately, I didn't
         give her a proper home.

265
00:23:58,203 --> 00:23:59,470
She was without supervision.

266
00:23:59,472 --> 00:24:03,807
So she joined a fast      
       international set.

267
00:24:03,809 --> 00:24:05,308
One scandal after another.

268
00:24:05,310 --> 00:24:08,846
When I disapproved,       
    cut off her allowance...

269
00:24:10,248 --> 00:24:15,285
...she committed some greater  
       folly to spite me.

270
00:24:18,357 --> 00:24:20,491
Yet, behind her bravado,

271
00:24:20,493 --> 00:24:22,860
something was eating away
              at her soul.

272
00:24:22,862 --> 00:24:25,578
This can happen 
               to men and women.

273
00:24:25,580 --> 00:24:28,215
They burn the heart
              out of themselves

274
00:24:28,217 --> 00:24:29,416
by living too greedily,

275
00:24:29,418 --> 00:24:30,884
and suddenly...

276
00:24:34,457 --> 00:24:35,455
...all is finished.

277
00:24:35,457 --> 00:24:36,924
Why are you telling me this?

278
00:24:36,926 --> 00:24:37,925
Without telling me,

279
00:24:37,927 --> 00:24:39,359
she married   
               an Italian count,

280
00:24:39,361 --> 00:24:40,978
who killed himself

281
00:24:40,980 --> 00:24:44,114
in a Maserati with one     
       of his mistresses.

282
00:24:44,116 --> 00:24:47,101
I gave her too much,      
  and it brought her nothing.

283
00:24:47,103 --> 00:24:49,936
Now, why I tell you all this.

284
00:24:52,541 --> 00:24:56,443
I've been informed of everything
  you've done for my daughter.

285
00:24:56,445 --> 00:24:57,744
Everything?

286
00:24:57,746 --> 00:25:00,447
Don't worry.     
         Don't worry about that.

287
00:25:00,449 --> 00:25:02,949
What you did,   
            the way you behaved,

288
00:25:02,951 --> 00:25:06,386
might be the beginning 
        of some kind of therapy.

289
00:25:06,388 --> 00:25:08,288
She needs help.

290
00:25:10,259 --> 00:25:11,391
Your help.

291
00:25:12,328 --> 00:25:13,960
I find her fascinating,

292
00:25:13,962 --> 00:25:15,895
but she needs a psychiatrist,
              not me.

293
00:25:15,897 --> 00:25:19,466
What she needs is a man         
to dominate her!

294
00:25:19,468 --> 00:25:22,369
To make love to her enough      
to make her love him.

295
00:25:23,639 --> 00:25:25,172
A man like you.

296
00:25:26,775 --> 00:25:28,575
You overestimate me,
                   Draco.

297
00:25:28,577 --> 00:25:31,345
She's very attractive,          
but what you ask is not for me.

298
00:25:33,015 --> 00:25:34,248
Mm.

299
00:25:36,718 --> 00:25:39,786
Listen to me.        
      On the day you marry her,

300
00:25:39,788 --> 00:25:44,474
I'll give you a personal dowry
  of one million pounds in gold.

301
00:25:45,711 --> 00:25:47,945
That's quite an inducement.

302
00:25:49,414 --> 00:25:50,881
But I don't need            
    a million pounds.

303
00:25:50,883 --> 00:25:53,049
<i> Stupido!</i>

304
00:25:53,051 --> 00:25:54,951
And I have a bachelor's         
taste for freedom.

305
00:25:54,953 --> 00:25:58,389
Please, just see her some more.

306
00:25:58,391 --> 00:25:59,956
Who knows what will come of it?

307
00:25:59,958 --> 00:26:02,325
I'm sorry, Draco,               
but in my profession, I can't--

308
00:26:02,327 --> 00:26:04,127
What?

309
00:26:04,129 --> 00:26:06,897
You have connections            
not open to me.

310
00:26:06,899 --> 00:26:09,065
Where is Ernst Stavro Blofeld?

311
00:26:10,369 --> 00:26:12,002
Blofeld?

312
00:26:12,004 --> 00:26:13,203
[CHUCKLES]

313
00:26:13,205 --> 00:26:15,071
Some of my men have recently
          defected to him.

314
00:26:15,073 --> 00:26:16,774
I don't know where he is.

315
00:26:16,776 --> 00:26:18,776
Can you find out?

316
00:26:18,778 --> 00:26:23,547
If I could, I wouldn't tell 
   Her Majesty's Secret Service.

317
00:26:23,549 --> 00:26:27,551
But I might tell  
           my future son-in-law.

318
00:26:27,553 --> 00:26:28,752
Go on.

319
00:26:30,890 --> 00:26:33,724
Next week is my birthday.

320
00:26:33,726 --> 00:26:36,527
For that,           
 Teresa always comes back to me.

321
00:26:41,033 --> 00:26:42,533
You understand?

322
00:26:42,535 --> 00:26:45,101
Let's say                
I'll sleep on the idea.

323
00:26:45,103 --> 00:26:46,103
You do that.

324
00:26:48,240 --> 00:26:50,440
James, where have you been?

325
00:26:50,442 --> 00:26:53,010
Much too far from you, darling.

326
00:26:53,012 --> 00:26:54,645
Oh, same old James.

327
00:26:54,647 --> 00:26:55,979
Ooh!

328
00:26:55,981 --> 00:26:57,814
Only more so.

329
00:26:57,816 --> 00:26:59,382
Heartless brute,

330
00:26:59,384 --> 00:27:01,785
letting me pine away  
        without even a postcard.

331
00:27:01,787 --> 00:27:04,320
Pine no more.

332
00:27:04,322 --> 00:27:08,191
[WHISPERS]                      
Cocktails at my place,          
8-ish, just the two of us.

333
00:27:08,193 --> 00:27:13,429
Oh, I'd adore that,     
   if only I could trust myself.

334
00:27:13,431 --> 00:27:16,099
Same old Moneypenny,            
Britain's last line of defense.

335
00:27:16,101 --> 00:27:17,100
[CHUCKLING]

336
00:27:17,102 --> 00:27:18,268
You'd better go in.

337
00:27:18,270 --> 00:27:20,904
He's running      
        a very tight ship today.

338
00:27:20,906 --> 00:27:22,172
[CLEARS THROAT]

339
00:27:38,190 --> 00:27:40,774
I'm relieving you from          
Operation Bedlam, 007.

340
00:27:40,776 --> 00:27:44,828
But, sir, Blofeld's    
    something of a must with me.

341
00:27:44,830 --> 00:27:46,964
You've had two years            
  to run him down.

342
00:27:46,966 --> 00:27:48,966
Does this mean you've
          lost confidence in me?

343
00:27:48,968 --> 00:27:51,468
I am well aware              
of your talents, 007,

344
00:27:51,470 --> 00:27:53,137
but license to kill is useless

345
00:27:53,139 --> 00:27:54,755
unless one can set up           
     the target.

346
00:27:54,757 --> 00:27:56,556
I'll find you a more            
suitable assignment.

347
00:27:56,558 --> 00:27:57,590
Sir, under the circum--

348
00:27:57,592 --> 00:27:58,676
That's all.           
          That's all.

349
00:28:03,265 --> 00:28:04,948
[♪♪♪]

350
00:28:09,438 --> 00:28:11,205
That was a quick conference.

351
00:28:11,207 --> 00:28:13,707
How do you expect a girl        
to keep herself alluring?

352
00:28:13,709 --> 00:28:15,192
Take a memo, please,
                 Moneypenny.

353
00:28:18,114 --> 00:28:19,146
Ready, James.

354
00:28:19,148 --> 00:28:21,381
Sir,              
  I have the honor to request

355
00:28:21,383 --> 00:28:25,719
you will accept my resignation,
       effective forthwith.

356
00:28:27,372 --> 00:28:28,405
Resignation from what?

357
00:28:28,407 --> 00:28:30,340
Her Majesty's Secret Service.

358
00:28:30,342 --> 00:28:33,010
And kindly present it  
      to that monument in there.

359
00:28:33,012 --> 00:28:34,678
[DOOR OPENS]

360
00:28:34,680 --> 00:28:35,795
[DOOR SLAMS]

361
00:28:56,068 --> 00:28:58,869
<i> ♪ Underneath the mango tree ♪</i>

362
00:28:58,871 --> 00:29:02,906
<i> ♪ Me honey and me</i>       
   <i> Can watch for the moon ♪</i>

363
00:29:02,908 --> 00:29:05,776
[THEME FROM "FROM RUSSIA    
      WITH LOVE" PLAYING]

364
00:29:09,498 --> 00:29:11,931
[THEME FROM "THUNDERBALL"    
            PLAYING]

365
00:29:20,158 --> 00:29:21,658
Sorry, ma'am.

366
00:29:23,295 --> 00:29:25,011
[PHONE BUZZES]

367
00:29:27,082 --> 00:29:28,599
007--      
               James Bond, here.

368
00:29:28,601 --> 00:29:30,384
He wants you, James.

369
00:29:42,113 --> 00:29:43,146
Request granted.

370
00:29:56,428 --> 00:29:59,262
Request granted.                
Not even "with regret."

371
00:29:59,264 --> 00:30:02,632
What did you expect,
                a knighthood?

372
00:30:02,634 --> 00:30:04,133
Why don't you read it.

373
00:30:06,672 --> 00:30:08,438
"Two weeks leave."

374
00:30:08,440 --> 00:30:12,442
Well, you didn't really
        want to resign, did you?

375
00:30:12,444 --> 00:30:15,779
Moneypenny,                     
what would I do without you?

376
00:30:15,781 --> 00:30:18,782
My problem is that you  
      never do anything with me.

377
00:30:18,784 --> 00:30:20,951
It's a date.               
The moment I get back.

378
00:30:20,953 --> 00:30:22,285
Where are you off to?

379
00:30:22,287 --> 00:30:23,954
Just someplace to laze about.

380
00:30:24,990 --> 00:30:26,490
Beachcombing.

381
00:30:28,927 --> 00:30:29,926
[DOOR SHUTS]

382
00:30:29,928 --> 00:30:31,761
[INTERCOM BEEPS]

383
00:30:31,763 --> 00:30:35,282
M:               
 <i> What would</i> I<i> do without you,</i>  
  <i> Ms. Moneypenny? Thank you.</i>

384
00:30:35,284 --> 00:30:37,201
[♪♪♪]

385
00:30:51,884 --> 00:30:53,516
[CHILDREN SINGING]

386
00:30:55,220 --> 00:30:56,253
<i> Bonjour,</i> Miguel.

387
00:31:03,795 --> 00:31:05,328
[BULL MOOING]

388
00:31:09,418 --> 00:31:11,184
[CROWD CHEERING]

389
00:31:16,291 --> 00:31:17,390
[CROWD CHEERING]

390
00:31:17,392 --> 00:31:19,993
[MOOING]

391
00:31:19,995 --> 00:31:21,761
WOMAN: Teresa.   
            TRACY: Good morning.

392
00:31:21,763 --> 00:31:23,914
WOMAN:       
             It's been so long  
           since we've seen you.

393
00:31:23,916 --> 00:31:25,348
[BULL ROARING]

394
00:31:28,754 --> 00:31:29,753
Yes, very well.

395
00:31:29,755 --> 00:31:30,754
There's Tracy.

396
00:31:30,756 --> 00:31:32,356
Huh?              
     Tracy.

397
00:31:32,358 --> 00:31:35,676
Where is she?          
       Ah, there she is.

398
00:31:35,678 --> 00:31:36,677
Teresa!

399
00:31:36,679 --> 00:31:38,645
Happy birthday, Papa.

400
00:31:38,647 --> 00:31:41,948
You make it so by being here.
        You look marvelous.

401
00:31:41,950 --> 00:31:44,151
There's someone      
    I want you to meet. Come on.

402
00:31:44,153 --> 00:31:45,686
<i> Salut,</i> Olympe, 
                 how are you?

403
00:31:45,688 --> 00:31:47,087
It's good to have you back.

404
00:31:49,158 --> 00:31:51,357
You look wonderful.       
               Thanks.

405
00:31:51,359 --> 00:31:53,327
WOMAN 2: Contessa.          
          <i> Bonjour.</i>

406
00:31:53,329 --> 00:31:56,896
Mr. Bond, may I introduce    
      my daughter, Teresa?

407
00:31:56,898 --> 00:31:58,282
Contessa.

408
00:31:58,284 --> 00:31:59,950
Mr. Bond and I have already met.

409
00:31:59,952 --> 00:32:01,735
But each time               
is a renewed pleasure.

410
00:32:03,088 --> 00:32:05,222
Madame always makes one         
   feel so welcome.

411
00:32:09,595 --> 00:32:11,695
She likes you. 
                 I can see it.

412
00:32:11,697 --> 00:32:13,797
You must give me the name       
    of your oculist.

413
00:32:13,799 --> 00:32:15,299
[CROWD CHEERING]

414
00:32:15,301 --> 00:32:16,966
Ho! Ho!

415
00:32:18,203 --> 00:32:20,220
[CROWD APPLAUDS]

416
00:32:20,222 --> 00:32:24,657
Olympe, I didn't know
            Mr. Bond knew Papa.

417
00:32:24,659 --> 00:32:25,926
I think                  
there are many things

418
00:32:25,928 --> 00:32:27,444
about Mr. Bond                
one does not know.

419
00:32:27,446 --> 00:32:28,578
It would be interesting

420
00:32:28,580 --> 00:32:30,914
to attend night school,     
            perhaps.

421
00:32:32,067 --> 00:32:33,900
Hyah!

422
00:32:33,902 --> 00:32:37,070
[CROWD CHEERING]

423
00:32:37,072 --> 00:32:40,506
Papa is up to something.
             I'm sure of it.

424
00:32:40,508 --> 00:32:42,743
Your father loves you      
       very much, Tracy.

425
00:32:42,745 --> 00:32:47,513
Whatever he may arrange,        
I know it's for your happiness.

426
00:32:47,515 --> 00:32:48,548
What<i> has</i>

427
00:32:48,550 --> 00:32:51,084
Papa arranged?

428
00:32:51,086 --> 00:32:54,721
[SHOUTING]

429
00:32:54,723 --> 00:32:56,039
[GRUNTS]

430
00:33:00,195 --> 00:33:02,462
[ALL SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY]

431
00:33:04,683 --> 00:33:07,050
Ah, Mr. Bond!

432
00:33:07,052 --> 00:33:08,451
Thank you.

433
00:33:08,453 --> 00:33:10,453
Many happy returns.

434
00:33:10,455 --> 00:33:12,055
The best years  
              are still to come,

435
00:33:12,057 --> 00:33:13,056
let's hope.

436
00:33:13,058 --> 00:33:15,275
Oh, allow me.

437
00:33:15,277 --> 00:33:16,860
What are you doing here?

438
00:33:16,862 --> 00:33:19,496
Yes, wasn't it kind       
  of your father to invite me?

439
00:33:19,498 --> 00:33:21,798
Mr. Bond and I are discussing
      a business deal, Teresa.

440
00:33:21,800 --> 00:33:22,833
Really?

441
00:33:22,835 --> 00:33:24,067
Mm-hm.

442
00:33:24,069 --> 00:33:26,686
No woman would waste          
this excellent champagne

443
00:33:26,688 --> 00:33:28,422
discussing a business deal.

444
00:33:28,424 --> 00:33:29,556
Unless of course,

445
00:33:29,558 --> 00:33:31,875
she happened to be part     
      of the arrangement.

446
00:33:31,877 --> 00:33:33,293
Olympe, what have you said?

447
00:33:33,295 --> 00:33:34,894
Don't blame Olympe, Papa.

448
00:33:34,896 --> 00:33:36,496
I'm not your daughter           
    for nothing.

449
00:33:36,498 --> 00:33:38,665
Hmm, I detect a certain
           family resemblance.

450
00:33:38,667 --> 00:33:41,501
I suggest you revise the terms  
of your contract, Mr. Bond.

451
00:33:41,503 --> 00:33:43,887
You'll find your liability      
far too expensive.

452
00:33:43,889 --> 00:33:46,089
Ah, now, there you're mistaken.

453
00:33:46,091 --> 00:33:47,274
Papa.                           
                    Yes?

454
00:33:47,276 --> 00:33:49,359
Mr. Bond wants         
       some information.

455
00:33:49,361 --> 00:33:50,927
I wonder            
   what you're talking about.

456
00:33:50,929 --> 00:33:52,495
You always taught me            
  that a good host

457
00:33:52,497 --> 00:33:53,864
supplies his guests' needs.

458
00:33:53,866 --> 00:33:55,032
Uh-huh.

459
00:33:55,034 --> 00:33:56,616
And without obligation.

460
00:33:58,454 --> 00:33:59,786
And then?

461
00:33:59,788 --> 00:34:01,954
I'm not sure "obligation"
        is quite the right word.

462
00:34:01,956 --> 00:34:03,373
Tell him, Papa.

463
00:34:03,375 --> 00:34:05,625
Tell him what                   
he wants to know.

464
00:34:05,627 --> 00:34:06,877
Now!

465
00:34:06,879 --> 00:34:08,829
Please. Please, Teresa.

466
00:34:08,831 --> 00:34:11,331
There's only a possibility.   
       Nothing definite.

467
00:34:11,333 --> 00:34:14,150
Tell him, Papa...        
 or you'll never see me again.

468
00:34:20,675 --> 00:34:21,941
All right.

469
00:34:23,595 --> 00:34:25,262
All right.

470
00:34:25,264 --> 00:34:28,147
There may be a connection
        between that man Blofeld

471
00:34:28,149 --> 00:34:32,335
and a lawyer with offices  
      in Bern, Switzerland...

472
00:34:33,906 --> 00:34:35,272
...named Gumbold.

473
00:34:35,274 --> 00:34:37,307
Gumbold.     
              Bern, Switzerland.

474
00:34:37,309 --> 00:34:38,525
Yes, Gumbold.

475
00:34:38,527 --> 00:34:40,693
So...

476
00:34:40,695 --> 00:34:42,913
Now Mr. Bond need have     
   no further interest in me.

477
00:34:42,915 --> 00:34:43,896
Another mistake.

478
00:34:45,367 --> 00:34:47,967
She always was         
      a headstrong child.

479
00:34:47,969 --> 00:34:50,236
I'm sorry, uh--

480
00:34:50,238 --> 00:34:51,922
Where has he gone?

481
00:34:51,924 --> 00:34:53,924
[SHOUTING]

482
00:34:53,926 --> 00:34:56,059
[CROWD CHEERING]

483
00:34:59,264 --> 00:35:00,497
Tracy!

484
00:35:07,439 --> 00:35:08,905
Tracy.

485
00:35:08,907 --> 00:35:12,709
I was always taught that        
mistakes should be remedied.

486
00:35:12,711 --> 00:35:14,544
Especially between friends.

487
00:35:14,546 --> 00:35:18,448
[LOUIS ARMSTRONG'S "WE HAVE ALL 
THE TIME IN THE WORLD" PLAYING]

488
00:35:18,450 --> 00:35:20,717
Or lovers.

489
00:35:20,719 --> 00:35:24,121
<i> ♪ We have all ♪</i>

490
00:35:24,123 --> 00:35:26,856
<i> ♪ The time ♪</i>

491
00:35:26,858 --> 00:35:30,960
<i> ♪ In the world ♪</i>

492
00:35:30,962 --> 00:35:37,467
<i> ♪ Time enough for life</i>     
          <i> To unfold ♪</i>

493
00:35:37,469 --> 00:35:42,705
<i> ♪ All the precious things </i>   
      <i> Love has in store ♪</i>

494
00:35:42,707 --> 00:35:46,042
<i> ♪ We have all ♪</i>

495
00:35:46,044 --> 00:35:48,444
<i> ♪ The love ♪</i>

496
00:35:48,446 --> 00:35:53,366
<i> ♪ In the world ♪</i>

497
00:35:53,368 --> 00:35:56,937
<i> ♪ If that's all we have ♪</i>

498
00:35:56,939 --> 00:35:59,138
<i> ♪ You will find ♪</i>

499
00:35:59,140 --> 00:36:04,343
<i> ♪ We need nothing more ♪</i>

500
00:36:04,345 --> 00:36:11,101
<i> ♪ Every step of the way ♪</i>

501
00:36:11,103 --> 00:36:15,738
<i> ♪ Will find us ♪</i>

502
00:36:15,740 --> 00:36:21,427
<i> ♪ With the cares of the world ♪</i>

503
00:36:21,429 --> 00:36:26,049
<i> ♪ Far behind us ♪</i>

504
00:36:26,051 --> 00:36:30,153
<i> ♪ We have all... ♪</i>

505
00:36:30,155 --> 00:36:35,008
<i> ♪ The time in the world ♪</i>

506
00:36:35,010 --> 00:36:38,445
<i> ♪ Just for love ♪</i>

507
00:36:38,447 --> 00:36:42,715
<i> ♪ Nothing more</i>         
        <i> Nothing less ♪</i>

508
00:36:42,717 --> 00:36:47,920
<i> ♪ Only love ♪</i>

509
00:36:47,922 --> 00:36:50,857
[♪♪♪]

510
00:37:12,363 --> 00:37:18,134
<i> ♪ Only love ♪</i>

511
00:37:23,674 --> 00:37:25,375
I'll get cracking        
      on this appointment,

512
00:37:25,377 --> 00:37:26,543
then catch up with you.

513
00:37:26,545 --> 00:37:28,144
TRACY:        
          The story of our life,
                  James?

514
00:37:28,146 --> 00:37:29,646
Just keep my martini cool.   
                          Ha-ha.

515
00:37:54,156 --> 00:37:55,722
[LOCK TURNS]

516
00:38:02,931 --> 00:38:07,934
[♪♪♪]

517
00:38:07,936 --> 00:38:09,468
I will be back in an hour.

518
00:38:09,470 --> 00:38:10,970
<i> Bon appétit,</i>                   
 <i> monsieur.</i>

519
00:38:19,681 --> 00:38:21,447
[SPEAKS             
           IN GERMAN]

520
00:38:33,712 --> 00:38:34,878
[TURNS LOCK]

521
00:38:45,607 --> 00:38:49,325
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

522
00:39:11,198 --> 00:39:14,133
[METAL CLANGING,        
        MOTORS WHIRRING]

523
00:40:23,839 --> 00:40:25,538
[HORNS HONKING]

524
00:40:25,540 --> 00:40:27,507
Such things should be left      
   to a girl's father,

525
00:40:27,509 --> 00:40:29,042
who knows what                 
is best for her.

526
00:40:29,044 --> 00:40:30,176
Papa.

527
00:40:30,178 --> 00:40:32,811
But what could be better
           than being in love?

528
00:40:34,182 --> 00:40:36,815
Mr. Bond is--                
Is in love with you?

529
00:40:39,187 --> 00:40:40,786
That may come too...

530
00:40:40,788 --> 00:40:42,955
someday.

531
00:40:42,957 --> 00:40:46,092
Life's too short                
for "someday," Teresa.

532
00:40:46,094 --> 00:40:47,260
Tomorrow--

533
00:40:47,262 --> 00:40:49,395
Tomorrow I will speak to him    
     alone, man-to-man.

534
00:40:49,397 --> 00:40:50,663
No, Papa.      
    Why not?

535
00:40:50,665 --> 00:40:52,231
No talk.

536
00:40:52,233 --> 00:40:55,201
Whatever happens,   
         there'll be no regrets.

537
00:40:57,072 --> 00:40:58,438
Please.

538
00:40:59,707 --> 00:41:00,857
Mm.

539
00:41:23,098 --> 00:41:24,113
[MACHINE BEEPS]

540
00:41:26,918 --> 00:41:28,468
[MACHINE BEEPS]

541
00:41:33,541 --> 00:41:34,540
[MACHINE BEEPS]

542
00:42:51,069 --> 00:42:55,271
[PEOPLE SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

543
00:43:29,841 --> 00:43:31,073
[TURNS LOCK]

544
00:43:35,663 --> 00:43:37,663
[PEOPLE CONVERSING       
           IN GERMAN]

545
00:44:13,451 --> 00:44:15,918
[RINGS DOORBELL]

546
00:44:17,655 --> 00:44:18,788
Good afternoon.

547
00:44:18,790 --> 00:44:20,690
Good afternoon, Hammond.
           Is the admiral in?

548
00:44:20,692 --> 00:44:21,690
Certainly, sir.

549
00:44:25,196 --> 00:44:26,195
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

550
00:44:26,197 --> 00:44:27,997
Hmm?

551
00:44:27,999 --> 00:44:30,098
Excuse me, sir.         
   Commander Bond to see you.

552
00:44:31,319 --> 00:44:32,502
Right. Show him in.

553
00:44:32,504 --> 00:44:34,169
Aye, aye, sir.            
    If you please, sir.

554
00:44:34,171 --> 00:44:35,505
Thank you.

555
00:44:43,048 --> 00:44:45,881
Unusually small for             
a<i> Nymphalis polychloros.</i>

556
00:44:48,219 --> 00:44:52,939
I wasn't aware that your   
 expertise included lepidoptery.

557
00:44:52,941 --> 00:44:55,308
What are you doing here?  
    I thought you were on leave.

558
00:44:55,310 --> 00:44:57,110
Genealogy, sir.               
Fascinating subject.

559
00:44:57,112 --> 00:45:00,679
Came across a letter           
from Gebrüder Gumbold,

560
00:45:00,681 --> 00:45:01,914
solicitors in Switzerland,

561
00:45:01,916 --> 00:45:04,984
to a certain Count            
Balthazar de Bleuchamp.

562
00:45:04,986 --> 00:45:06,785
De Bleuchamp?

563
00:45:06,787 --> 00:45:09,688
French form of Blofeld.

564
00:45:09,690 --> 00:45:12,024
You've been relieved from
         Operation Bedlam, 007,

565
00:45:12,026 --> 00:45:13,659
do you remember?

566
00:45:13,661 --> 00:45:15,495
I assumed you'd                 
reassign me, sir.

567
00:45:15,497 --> 00:45:18,131
This is a photostat copy        
      of a letter

568
00:45:18,133 --> 00:45:20,600
<i> addressed to our College of</i>  
 <i> Arms in the city of London...</i>

569
00:45:20,602 --> 00:45:22,935
<i> with the request that</i>     
  <i> they undertake to establish</i>

570
00:45:22,937 --> 00:45:25,204
<i> de Bleuchamp's claim</i>      
         <i> to the title.</i>

571
00:45:25,206 --> 00:45:26,506
<i> And Sir Hilary Bray--</i>

572
00:45:26,508 --> 00:45:28,508
<i> He's the sable basilisk</i>    
        <i> of the college.</i>

573
00:45:28,510 --> 00:45:29,942
<i> --has replied to Gumbold,</i>

574
00:45:29,944 --> 00:45:32,578
<i> suggesting that he should meet</i> 
    <i> de Bleuchamp in person.</i>

575
00:45:32,580 --> 00:45:34,614
<i> Now, I've already taken</i>    
       <i> the liberty, sir,</i>

576
00:45:34,616 --> 00:45:36,249
<i> of working</i>           
   <i> with the college on this,</i>

577
00:45:36,251 --> 00:45:39,101
<i> using an examination of my own</i> 
     <i> family tree as cover.</i>

578
00:45:39,103 --> 00:45:40,369
<i> I've also been reading up</i>

579
00:45:40,371 --> 00:45:42,271
<i> on the technical side</i>     
        <i> of heraldry...</i>

580
00:45:42,273 --> 00:45:44,640
Uh, Sir Hilary Bray, please.  
        Commander Bond.

581
00:45:44,642 --> 00:45:46,275
Ah, yes, sir.

582
00:45:46,277 --> 00:45:48,444
BOND:<i> </i>             
 <i> ...so that, should he consent</i> 
         <i> to a meeting,</i>

583
00:45:48,446 --> 00:45:51,380
<i> I could act as a representative</i>
        <i> of the college.</i>

584
00:45:51,382 --> 00:45:52,848
BRAY:<i> </i>
                          <i> Come.</i>

585
00:45:53,568 --> 00:45:54,567
Ah, good afternoon.

586
00:45:54,569 --> 00:45:55,835
Good afternoon,     
              Sir Hilary.

587
00:45:55,837 --> 00:45:56,836
Have a look at this.

588
00:45:56,838 --> 00:45:57,954
Now, let me take your coat.

589
00:45:57,956 --> 00:45:59,655
Arms of Sir Thomas Bond,

590
00:45:59,657 --> 00:46:02,124
Baronet of Peckham,
                  died 1734.

591
00:46:02,126 --> 00:46:05,127
Argent on a chevron sable.
            Three bezants.

592
00:46:05,129 --> 00:46:08,214
Good motto, eh?     
      "The World is Not Enough."

593
00:46:08,216 --> 00:46:09,615
Phidian's doing                 
a splendid job.

594
00:46:09,617 --> 00:46:11,550
Thank you,    
             Mr. Sable Basilisk.

595
00:46:11,552 --> 00:46:14,286
We've traced your line          
to a Sir Otho le Bon,

596
00:46:14,288 --> 00:46:16,021
who held the manor          
    of Wickhamsbreux

597
00:46:16,023 --> 00:46:17,223
by a knight's fee

598
00:46:17,225 --> 00:46:20,426
from the Earl of Thanet,    
             1387.

599
00:46:20,428 --> 00:46:21,960
We're in luck.

600
00:46:21,962 --> 00:46:23,829
Gumbold's telephoned            
     from Bern

601
00:46:23,831 --> 00:46:26,332
to say that his client has
         consented to see me.

602
00:46:26,334 --> 00:46:27,366
You mean me.

603
00:46:27,368 --> 00:46:28,367
Yes, you.

604
00:46:28,369 --> 00:46:30,569
But, Commander Bond,

605
00:46:30,571 --> 00:46:33,072
I'm only able to countenance
           this deception

606
00:46:33,074 --> 00:46:34,574
on your assurance    
            that the matter

607
00:46:34,576 --> 00:46:35,775
is of national
                    importance.

608
00:46:35,777 --> 00:46:36,876
I haven't exaggerated.

609
00:46:36,878 --> 00:46:38,944
My department appreciates       
your help very much.

610
00:46:38,946 --> 00:46:40,212
During the deception period,

611
00:46:40,214 --> 00:46:41,513
I've arranged        
           to lose myself

612
00:46:41,515 --> 00:46:43,182
amongst the churches      
          of Brittany.

613
00:46:43,184 --> 00:46:45,635
I want to do some      
   brass rubbings there, anyway.

614
00:46:45,637 --> 00:46:46,936
Where do I go             
    for this meeting?

615
00:46:46,938 --> 00:46:48,804
Well, they're being  
         a bit canny about that.

616
00:46:48,806 --> 00:46:50,289
They want a description
                of myself.

617
00:46:50,291 --> 00:46:52,041
Tactfully adjusted          
       to favor me.

618
00:46:52,043 --> 00:46:53,309
Yes.

619
00:46:53,311 --> 00:46:54,710
They will send the time
                and place

620
00:46:54,712 --> 00:46:56,279
from where I am to be, um...

621
00:46:56,281 --> 00:46:58,281
"collected," as they put it.

622
00:46:58,283 --> 00:47:01,934
It's not our sort of thing, 
   but under the circumstances--

623
00:47:01,936 --> 00:47:03,486
Sounds as if             
    they're suspicious.

624
00:47:03,488 --> 00:47:04,787
No, no, no.     
              Not suspicious.

625
00:47:04,789 --> 00:47:06,288
Just, uh, discreet.

626
00:47:06,290 --> 00:47:09,025
There was no objection  
      to my fee of 1000 guineas.

627
00:47:09,027 --> 00:47:11,110
Could their claim           
       be genuine?

628
00:47:11,112 --> 00:47:13,045
It's hard to say        
         at this point.

629
00:47:13,047 --> 00:47:14,480
Our methods are very exacting.

630
00:47:14,482 --> 00:47:17,282
We never like to speak     
 until we're absolutely certain

631
00:47:17,284 --> 00:47:19,384
there could be no possibility  
      of error on our side

632
00:47:19,386 --> 00:47:21,671
or forgery on anybody else's.

633
00:47:21,673 --> 00:47:23,673
I hope I can live up to     
      your high standards.

634
00:47:23,675 --> 00:47:25,741
Oh, one helpful physical point 
         might be that

635
00:47:25,743 --> 00:47:29,111
the real de Bleuchamps     
     are without earlobes.

636
00:47:29,113 --> 00:47:31,647
It's, uh, not the sort of thing
   that we rely on, of course,

637
00:47:31,649 --> 00:47:32,632
uh, but it could help.

638
00:47:32,634 --> 00:47:34,300
No earlobes.

639
00:47:34,302 --> 00:47:36,001
You might try inviting him
             to Augsburg.

640
00:47:36,003 --> 00:47:37,969
The de Bleuchamps have been
          coming from there

641
00:47:37,971 --> 00:47:39,055
for generations.

642
00:47:39,057 --> 00:47:40,222
Yes, if he is our man,

643
00:47:40,224 --> 00:47:42,058
I'd like to get him away    
       from Switzerland.

644
00:47:42,060 --> 00:47:44,293
[WHISTLE BLOWS]

645
00:47:47,698 --> 00:47:51,701
[MAN SPEAKING          
      INDISTINCTLY ON PA]

646
00:47:51,703 --> 00:47:53,102
[TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING]

647
00:47:58,493 --> 00:48:00,993
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

648
00:48:27,588 --> 00:48:29,554
[IN GERMAN ACCENT]              
Sir Hilary Bray, baronet?

649
00:48:29,556 --> 00:48:30,940
The same, dear lady.

650
00:48:30,942 --> 00:48:33,875
I am Fraülein Irma Bunt,    
personal secretary to the count.

651
00:48:33,877 --> 00:48:34,860
How do you do?

652
00:48:34,862 --> 00:48:36,362
Have you had a good journey?

653
00:48:36,364 --> 00:48:37,780
No, quite intolerable.

654
00:48:37,782 --> 00:48:39,448
I'm not a good traveler,
               I'm afraid.

655
00:48:39,450 --> 00:48:40,449
I'm sorry.

656
00:48:40,451 --> 00:48:42,518
Grunther will                   
take your luggage.

657
00:48:42,520 --> 00:48:43,568
No, I can manage.

658
00:48:43,570 --> 00:48:44,970
[IN GERMAN ACCENT]       
           I take it.

659
00:48:45,939 --> 00:48:47,506
You know Switzerland,
                Sir Hilary?

660
00:48:47,508 --> 00:48:49,174
I'm afraid not,       
            Fraülein--?

661
00:48:49,176 --> 00:48:50,392
Bunt.      
             Bunt.

662
00:48:50,394 --> 00:48:52,261
Interesting name                
for a genealogist.

663
00:48:52,263 --> 00:48:53,462
Are you from                    
a naval family?

664
00:48:53,464 --> 00:48:54,597
Naval?

665
00:48:54,599 --> 00:48:56,232
It's a nautical term,           
      you see,

666
00:48:56,234 --> 00:48:58,934
meaning the baggy or            
swollen parts of a sail.

667
00:48:58,936 --> 00:49:00,236
Nothing personal,               
   of course.

668
00:49:00,238 --> 00:49:01,604
Interesting.

669
00:49:01,606 --> 00:49:02,605
You speak German?

670
00:49:02,607 --> 00:49:04,039
I'm afraid not.

671
00:49:04,041 --> 00:49:05,207
French, perhaps?

672
00:49:05,209 --> 00:49:06,475
A little.                       
Where are we off to?

673
00:49:06,477 --> 00:49:08,944
You will not be disappointed.   
           Please?

674
00:49:12,650 --> 00:49:15,083
Like the bugs in a rug, yes?

675
00:49:15,085 --> 00:49:16,652
You are comfortable?

676
00:49:16,654 --> 00:49:18,086
Yes, indeed, fraülein.

677
00:49:18,088 --> 00:49:19,921
Your kindness is 
             quite overwhelming.

678
00:49:19,923 --> 00:49:20,940
Good.

679
00:49:38,926 --> 00:49:41,927
[SLEIGH BELLS RINGING]

680
00:49:49,587 --> 00:49:51,303
DRIVER:             
           Hup. Hup.

681
00:49:57,862 --> 00:49:59,695
[DRIVER SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

682
00:50:02,549 --> 00:50:04,449
So we are halfway.

683
00:50:04,451 --> 00:50:06,585
Now we will have    
            a little flight.

684
00:50:06,587 --> 00:50:08,553
I've never been in one          
of these things before.

685
00:50:08,555 --> 00:50:10,639
And first you must 
            your pipe knock off.

686
00:50:10,641 --> 00:50:12,974
"Knock out," you mean.

687
00:50:12,976 --> 00:50:14,976
I hope.

688
00:50:14,978 --> 00:50:17,313
Mind your head,
                   Sir Hilary.

689
00:50:17,315 --> 00:50:19,215
Please fasten                   
your safety belt.

690
00:50:19,217 --> 00:50:21,433
[HELICOPTER ENGINE STARTING]

691
00:50:26,724 --> 00:50:28,190
Now up into the Alps.

692
00:50:49,747 --> 00:50:53,749
[♪♪♪]

693
00:51:11,903 --> 00:51:14,637
That is avalanche damage.

694
00:51:35,793 --> 00:51:38,610
You enjoy the skiing,      
    or the bobsled, perhaps?

695
00:51:38,612 --> 00:51:41,263
I'm not a sporting man,     
           fraülein.

696
00:51:41,265 --> 00:51:43,432
Even when I'm at my best.

697
00:51:44,635 --> 00:51:46,268
Do you feel           
        the airsickness?

698
00:52:05,590 --> 00:52:07,289
Up to there           
       is for the public,

699
00:52:07,291 --> 00:52:10,743
and from here upwards      
    it is strictly private.

700
00:52:10,745 --> 00:52:13,078
No one, no one at all

701
00:52:13,080 --> 00:52:15,847
may come through without    
   permission from the count.

702
00:52:15,849 --> 00:52:21,136
There is the Bleuchamp Institute
for Allergy Research.

703
00:52:22,673 --> 00:52:24,223
What kind of allergies?

704
00:52:24,225 --> 00:52:25,591
All of them.

705
00:52:25,593 --> 00:52:26,958
Like the hay fever,

706
00:52:26,960 --> 00:52:29,394
or the sickness caused     
        by the oysters,

707
00:52:29,396 --> 00:52:31,230
or inability to eat meat.

708
00:52:31,232 --> 00:52:34,366
The count is a great specialist 
in this field.

709
00:52:43,277 --> 00:52:45,411
I'll be glad to get my feet   
         on the ground.

710
00:52:45,413 --> 00:52:47,496
Not ground. Ice.

711
00:53:18,646 --> 00:53:23,414
[♪♪♪]

712
00:53:23,416 --> 00:53:26,451
Fraülein, I should warn you,
     guns make me very nervous.

713
00:53:26,453 --> 00:53:29,587
They are to keep away the spies 
from the chemical companies.

714
00:53:29,589 --> 00:53:31,289
Many times already              
 they have tried

715
00:53:31,291 --> 00:53:33,224
to steal our discoveries.

716
00:53:33,226 --> 00:53:35,761
Yes, we live in a world     
     of avarice and deceit.

717
00:53:35,763 --> 00:53:37,529
Here at least          
         is no avarice.

718
00:53:37,531 --> 00:53:38,864
Really?

719
00:53:38,866 --> 00:53:41,900
The Bleuchamp Institute     
 is not for profit, Sir Hilary.

720
00:53:41,902 --> 00:53:43,501
[HIGH-PITCHED TONE WARBLING]

721
00:53:43,503 --> 00:53:46,471
The count does his work     
    for the sake of mankind.

722
00:53:46,473 --> 00:53:48,623
I'm very happy         
          to hear it.

723
00:53:48,625 --> 00:53:51,626
He wants to leave his mark      
on the entire world.

724
00:53:51,628 --> 00:53:52,827
Characteristic         
           ambition.

725
00:53:52,829 --> 00:53:54,563
Characteristic?

726
00:53:54,565 --> 00:53:55,630
Of a true                 
    humanitarian.

727
00:53:55,632 --> 00:53:56,649
Oh.

728
00:53:56,651 --> 00:53:58,784
Formerly it was
                  a sports club,

729
00:53:58,786 --> 00:54:00,119
open to the public.

730
00:54:00,121 --> 00:54:01,419
Now it belongs to
                   the count,

731
00:54:01,421 --> 00:54:05,074
who has given it             
to scientific research.

732
00:54:05,076 --> 00:54:07,809
Joseph, Sir Hilary Bray     
     will take number four.

733
00:54:07,811 --> 00:54:10,612
I will show you there      
  after Grunther has taken you

734
00:54:10,614 --> 00:54:12,264
for medical examination.

735
00:54:12,266 --> 00:54:13,415
I'm quite all right now.

736
00:54:13,417 --> 00:54:15,583
You are our honored guest,
              Sir Hilary.

737
00:54:15,585 --> 00:54:16,818
Thank you.

738
00:54:16,820 --> 00:54:19,021
And after your experience
          in the helicopter...

739
00:54:19,023 --> 00:54:22,174
we must make sure that   
    you are entirely well again.

740
00:54:22,176 --> 00:54:24,877
Grunther, take Sir Hilary
            to Dr. Von Sant.

741
00:54:24,879 --> 00:54:26,011
GRUNTHER:<i> </i>  
                  <i> Ja, fraülein.</i>

742
00:54:32,386 --> 00:54:33,802
Director,<i> bitte.</i>

743
00:54:33,804 --> 00:54:34,836
[PHONE RINGS]

744
00:54:37,240 --> 00:54:39,608
Yes?                  
    [BUNT SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

745
00:54:39,610 --> 00:54:41,193
Provide him with                
the usual comforts.

746
00:54:41,195 --> 00:54:42,828
<i> Ja.</i>

747
00:54:43,564 --> 00:54:45,798
You have 10 minutes.

748
00:54:45,800 --> 00:54:47,265
And then take them
                to number four.

749
00:54:47,267 --> 00:54:48,484
<i> Ja.</i>

750
00:54:54,192 --> 00:54:56,508
If you wish anything            
 for your comfort,

751
00:54:56,510 --> 00:54:57,827
you must ring this...

752
00:54:57,829 --> 00:55:00,195
[BEEPS]             
...and the attendant will come.

753
00:55:00,197 --> 00:55:02,197
Very considerate.
                   Thank you.

754
00:55:02,199 --> 00:55:04,199
You must also               
    ring for him

755
00:55:04,201 --> 00:55:06,702
to open the door   
         when you wish to leave.

756
00:55:06,704 --> 00:55:08,587
Rather complicated              
   arrangement.

757
00:55:08,589 --> 00:55:10,956
To stop patients        
       leaving the rooms

758
00:55:10,958 --> 00:55:13,375
and disturbing each other 
    when they should be resting.

759
00:55:13,377 --> 00:55:17,596
The count believes very strongly
      in undisturbed rest.

760
00:55:17,598 --> 00:55:18,863
Prudent fellow.

761
00:55:18,865 --> 00:55:20,966
When can I see him?             
We have a great deal to discuss.

762
00:55:20,968 --> 00:55:23,485
He will send for you,   
    Sir Hilary, when he's ready.

763
00:55:23,487 --> 00:55:26,121
Meanwhile, I should very much
      like for you to join me

764
00:55:26,123 --> 00:55:27,622
in the Alpine Room     
           before dinner.

765
00:55:28,860 --> 00:55:29,992
Alpine Room?

766
00:55:29,994 --> 00:55:32,027
Yes. Grunther                 
will come for you.

767
00:55:32,029 --> 00:55:34,029
Shall we say 7:00?

768
00:55:34,031 --> 00:55:35,246
Thank you.

769
00:55:40,687 --> 00:55:44,139
[♪♪♪]

770
00:56:17,591 --> 00:56:20,459
[HELICOPTER BLADES WHIRRING   
          IN DISTANCE]

771
00:57:08,125 --> 00:57:10,692
[MOTOR WHIRRING]

772
00:57:10,694 --> 00:57:11,727
[BELL CHIMES]

773
00:57:19,837 --> 00:57:21,954
Fraülein Bunt                   
will receive you.

774
00:57:29,679 --> 00:57:32,780
[WOMEN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

775
00:57:35,819 --> 00:57:39,087
[♪♪♪]

776
00:57:51,252 --> 00:57:52,384
[CLEARS THROAT]

777
00:57:55,790 --> 00:57:59,991
Ah, Sir Hilary, please,        
come to meet our patients.

778
00:57:59,993 --> 00:58:01,793
Ladies, this is            
Sir Hilary Bray, baronet.

779
00:58:01,795 --> 00:58:03,311
How do you do?

780
00:58:03,313 --> 00:58:07,516
He's a famous genealogist.   
  You will have a drink, yes?

781
00:58:07,518 --> 00:58:09,351
Please,                    
come and sit down.

782
00:58:09,353 --> 00:58:10,835
How do you do?

783
00:58:10,837 --> 00:58:12,137
Thank you.

784
00:58:12,139 --> 00:58:13,555
What is a baronet?

785
00:58:13,557 --> 00:58:15,607
It's a kind of inferior     
         sort of baron.

786
00:58:15,609 --> 00:58:17,242
Oh, how disappointing.

787
00:58:17,244 --> 00:58:18,927
BOND:              
           Well, uh--

788
00:58:18,929 --> 00:58:20,378
Oh, I don't mean        
        you're inferior.

789
00:58:20,380 --> 00:58:21,563
I mean the title is.

790
00:58:21,565 --> 00:58:23,866
What's a gyn--? Genealogist?
            What is that?

791
00:58:23,868 --> 00:58:25,784
Palmy word for an old
              people's doctor.

792
00:58:25,786 --> 00:58:28,553
Ah, so he's here to cure        
     Fraülein Bunt?

793
00:58:28,555 --> 00:58:31,123
Watch yourself. She's got ears
         like an elephant.

794
00:58:31,125 --> 00:58:32,257
What will you drink,
                    sir?

795
00:58:32,259 --> 00:58:35,461
Malt whiskey          
   and branch water, please.

796
00:58:35,463 --> 00:58:38,213
Hey, I'm sorry I was so rude    
  about what a baronet is.

797
00:58:38,215 --> 00:58:39,798
You gave a very accurate
              description.

798
00:58:39,800 --> 00:58:41,566
[GIGGLES]

799
00:58:41,568 --> 00:58:42,751
ATTENDANT:
                         Sir.

800
00:58:42,753 --> 00:58:44,670
Thank you.

801
00:58:44,672 --> 00:58:46,922
I say, it's a treat,            
having a man here for once.

802
00:58:46,924 --> 00:58:49,357
Uh, you mean          
    there aren't any others?

803
00:58:49,359 --> 00:58:51,860
Only the staff, and you can't   
really count them.

804
00:58:51,862 --> 00:58:54,012
We do not discuss    
      our affairs of the clinic.

805
00:58:54,014 --> 00:58:57,066
Yes, but what is a genealogist? 
      Will nobody tell me?

806
00:58:57,068 --> 00:58:58,484
It would give me        
        great pleasure.

807
00:58:58,486 --> 00:58:59,935
Well?

808
00:58:59,937 --> 00:59:03,038
Genealogy is all about     
    ancestors and families.

809
00:59:03,040 --> 00:59:05,874
I mean, it could easily be   
    that any one of you here

810
00:59:05,876 --> 00:59:08,610
is related           
      to a royal house...

811
00:59:08,612 --> 00:59:11,413
if only we could go back    
    far enough to find out.

812
00:59:11,415 --> 00:59:13,332
Now, if you will tell me    
          your names--

813
00:59:13,334 --> 00:59:16,835
We do not use surnames here.  
  It is a rule of the clinic.

814
00:59:16,837 --> 00:59:19,370
Oh, I'm so sorry.        
      I didn't know that.

815
00:59:19,372 --> 00:59:22,206
Come, it's time   
                for dinner.

816
00:59:22,208 --> 00:59:26,210
Our schedule is rather strict.
          So is our diet.

817
00:59:26,212 --> 00:59:28,146
Please, Hilary,         
     if you would sit there

818
00:59:28,148 --> 00:59:29,714
between Helen and Ruby.

819
00:59:29,716 --> 00:59:33,018
I'm afraid I've never had much 
    to do with young ladies.

820
00:59:33,020 --> 00:59:35,721
I have ordered you
             a steak Piz Gloria.

821
00:59:35,723 --> 00:59:37,088
I hope you enjoy it.

822
00:59:37,090 --> 00:59:38,757
Thank you.                
   I'm sure I will.

823
00:59:38,759 --> 00:59:40,826
WOMAN:                
Can I have some ice water?

824
00:59:40,828 --> 00:59:42,394
Thank you so much.

825
00:59:42,396 --> 00:59:44,613
WOMAN 2:    
               Oh, this is good.

826
00:59:44,615 --> 00:59:47,149
HELEN:                  
     Are you here               
for Christmas, Hilary?

827
00:59:47,151 --> 00:59:49,568
Uh, well, I might be, if--

828
00:59:49,570 --> 00:59:52,103
Oh, good, then we can         
have a party before we go.

829
00:59:52,105 --> 00:59:54,273
BOND:              
       That sort of thing       
    is not quite in my line.

830
00:59:55,476 --> 00:59:56,658
Delicious!

831
00:59:56,660 --> 00:59:57,825
I used to hate chicken.

832
00:59:57,827 --> 00:59:59,578
Used to make me break out,
           it was all over.

833
00:59:59,580 --> 01:00:02,080
You'd be surprised where.

834
01:00:02,082 --> 01:00:04,249
Mm! Potatoes did it to me.      
Now I adore them.

835
01:00:04,251 --> 01:00:06,117
No medical histories,   
               please.

836
01:00:09,390 --> 01:00:12,174
Now, girls, I'm sure Sir Hilary 
would like to tell us

837
01:00:12,176 --> 01:00:14,343
about the College of Arms       
in London.

838
01:00:14,345 --> 01:00:16,929
RUBY:      
              Go on, Sir Hilary.
                Please tell us.

839
01:00:16,931 --> 01:00:18,730
If you'd really enjoy that.

840
01:00:18,732 --> 01:00:20,566
RUBY:                        
Please. Yes!

841
01:00:20,568 --> 01:00:22,417
WOMAN 2:            
     We promise to listen.

842
01:00:22,419 --> 01:00:24,269
[WOMEN CHATTERING]

843
01:00:24,271 --> 01:00:26,104
WOMAN 1:            
 Come on, tell us all about it.

844
01:00:26,106 --> 01:00:28,657
The Heralds' College,      
      or College of Arms,

845
01:00:28,659 --> 01:00:32,027
consists of 13 members     
     of the royal household

846
01:00:32,029 --> 01:00:34,329
appointed by the sovereign   
         to superintend

847
01:00:34,331 --> 01:00:37,449
armorial, genealogical,     
 ceremonial and other matters.

848
01:00:37,451 --> 01:00:39,368
WOMEN:             
             Mm-hm?

849
01:00:39,370 --> 01:00:42,120
The 13 members are divided   
     into three categories:

850
01:00:42,122 --> 01:00:45,724
kings, heralds and pursuivants.

851
01:00:45,726 --> 01:00:48,526
Their titles and offices    
    are of great antiquity.

852
01:00:48,528 --> 01:00:49,827
How compelling.

853
01:00:49,829 --> 01:00:53,164
When I tell you that the first 
    Clarenceux King of Arms

854
01:00:53,166 --> 01:00:56,334
was created in 1334...

855
01:00:56,336 --> 01:01:01,005
and the first          
    Somerset Herald in 1448.

856
01:01:01,007 --> 01:01:03,675
Now, when we authorize     
         a coat of arms

857
01:01:03,677 --> 01:01:06,144
it can include all sorts    
        of funny things.

858
01:01:06,146 --> 01:01:08,513
Crescent moons, portcullises,

859
01:01:08,515 --> 01:01:12,417
beasts couchant are rampant,  
        bars, bezants--

860
01:01:12,419 --> 01:01:14,369
Please, what is "bezant"?

861
01:01:15,539 --> 01:01:17,406
Gold balls.

862
01:01:19,460 --> 01:01:21,043
I brought a book        
        on the subject.

863
01:01:21,045 --> 01:01:23,328
There's a picture of my own     
  coat of arms, actually.

864
01:01:23,330 --> 01:01:25,581
Which includes four of them...

865
01:01:25,583 --> 01:01:27,549
[WOMEN GASP]

866
01:01:27,551 --> 01:01:29,718
...if you'd care to see them.

867
01:01:29,720 --> 01:01:31,837
I'd love to. I'm in room--

868
01:01:31,839 --> 01:01:33,805
No, no.             
  He will give the book to me.

869
01:01:33,807 --> 01:01:37,226
I will pass it         
      to everyone in turn.

870
01:01:37,228 --> 01:01:39,561
It is fairer          
        like that, yes?

871
01:01:39,563 --> 01:01:42,431
Of course.              
If you think so, fraülein.

872
01:01:43,867 --> 01:01:46,618
[WOMEN CHATTERING]

873
01:01:56,063 --> 01:01:58,547
Is anything the matter,     
          Sir Hilary?

874
01:02:00,250 --> 01:02:03,452
Just a slight stiffness     
  coming on...in the shoulder.

875
01:02:03,454 --> 01:02:06,020
Due to the altitude,            
     no doubt.

876
01:02:07,241 --> 01:02:09,807
[SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

877
01:02:09,809 --> 01:02:12,261
The count will see you now.   
    Grunther will take you.

878
01:02:12,263 --> 01:02:15,046
Thank you.           
   Please excuse me, ladies.

879
01:02:17,784 --> 01:02:21,085
May all your allergies     
       be swiftly cured.

880
01:02:23,957 --> 01:02:25,891
WOMAN:             
        What a nice man.

881
01:02:25,893 --> 01:02:27,025
WOMAN 3:        
                 Sweet.

882
01:02:27,027 --> 01:02:30,195
[WOMEN CHATTERING]

883
01:02:30,197 --> 01:02:32,046
Of course,         
   I know what he's allergic to.

884
01:02:34,768 --> 01:02:36,151
Bezants.

885
01:02:36,153 --> 01:02:39,254
[♪♪♪]

886
01:02:39,256 --> 01:02:40,588
[BELL CHIMES]

887
01:02:45,529 --> 01:02:48,530
[FOOTSTEPS ECHOING]

888
01:02:57,807 --> 01:03:00,008
[WATER DRIPPING]

889
01:03:05,482 --> 01:03:07,516
[BUZZING, CRACKLING]

890
01:03:07,518 --> 01:03:09,684
Antisepsis.

891
01:03:11,087 --> 01:03:13,154
[ELECTRONIC BEEPING]

892
01:03:30,390 --> 01:03:31,990
Please wait here.

893
01:03:44,271 --> 01:03:45,903
[HIGH-PITCHED RINGING]

894
01:03:49,826 --> 01:03:51,593
Good evening, Sir Hilary.

895
01:03:51,595 --> 01:03:52,661
Good evening.

896
01:03:52,663 --> 01:03:54,563
Balthazar, Count de Bleuchamp.

897
01:03:54,565 --> 01:03:56,565
If you'll forgive me,

898
01:03:56,567 --> 01:03:57,949
that's what I'm here            
    to find out.

899
01:03:57,951 --> 01:03:59,517
To confirm, Sir Hilary.

900
01:03:59,519 --> 01:04:00,986
There can be no doubt      
         of the truth.

901
01:04:00,988 --> 01:04:02,320
Please, sit down.

902
01:04:02,322 --> 01:04:03,822
If there were no doubt,

903
01:04:03,824 --> 01:04:06,191
I'm sure the College of Arms    
would not have sent me.

904
01:04:06,193 --> 01:04:07,859
Well, since you are here,

905
01:04:07,861 --> 01:04:10,528
I'll make everything
             very plain to you.

906
01:04:12,032 --> 01:04:15,834
To begin with,       
    I was born without earlobes.

907
01:04:15,836 --> 01:04:17,501
A well-known congenital
               distinction

908
01:04:17,503 --> 01:04:19,838
of Bleuchamp ancestry

909
01:04:19,840 --> 01:04:23,842
like the Hapsburg lip      
or the hawk nose of the Medicis.

910
01:04:23,844 --> 01:04:27,429
Granted, but the fact that      
you're of de Bleuchamp ancestry

911
01:04:27,431 --> 01:04:29,697
doesn't necessarily make you    
the reigning count.

912
01:04:29,699 --> 01:04:31,733
I feel it in my blood 
             and in my bones.

913
01:04:31,735 --> 01:04:33,000
I'm afraid the College of Arms

914
01:04:33,002 --> 01:04:34,770
will require                
more concrete proofs.

915
01:04:34,772 --> 01:04:36,872
And it shall have them.

916
01:04:36,874 --> 01:04:39,107
I have assembled     
     all the relevant documents:

917
01:04:39,109 --> 01:04:42,444
Title deeds, certificates
          of birth and death.

918
01:04:42,446 --> 01:04:45,046
They'll be sent to your room
         for authentication.

919
01:04:45,048 --> 01:04:48,166
You've only to ask Fraülein Bunt
    for anything you require.

920
01:04:48,168 --> 01:04:50,585
Are you        
         quite comfortable here?

921
01:04:50,587 --> 01:04:52,454
Yes, thank you,           
but puzzled by your clinic.

922
01:04:52,456 --> 01:04:55,356
Hm. Well, the methods  
         of the great pioneers

923
01:04:55,358 --> 01:04:57,842
have often puzzled    
          conventional minds.

924
01:04:57,844 --> 01:04:59,795
I've devised a cure
                for allergies

925
01:04:59,797 --> 01:05:03,364
which depends on holding
               an unusual

926
01:05:03,366 --> 01:05:05,901
and rather delicate 
          psychological balance.

927
01:05:05,903 --> 01:05:07,502
So, you see, I must impose

928
01:05:07,504 --> 01:05:10,104
rather special      
      conditions on my patients.

929
01:05:10,106 --> 01:05:11,405
And, um...

930
01:05:11,407 --> 01:05:12,691
your laboratories?

931
01:05:12,693 --> 01:05:15,894
The cure is not entirely 
      psychological, Sir Hilary.

932
01:05:15,896 --> 01:05:18,063
There are special vaccines
            to be prepared.

933
01:05:18,065 --> 01:05:21,733
Vaccines which must be modified
  to suit each individual case.

934
01:05:21,735 --> 01:05:23,735
So, you see,     
           I'm a very busy man

935
01:05:23,737 --> 01:05:25,904
and I might not be able
               to spare you

936
01:05:25,906 --> 01:05:27,305
as much of my time              
 as I might wish.

937
01:05:27,307 --> 01:05:29,407
If you wish to be confirmed
        as Count de Bleuchamp,

938
01:05:29,409 --> 01:05:31,409
you must give me 
              some of your time.

939
01:05:31,411 --> 01:05:33,378
I must have details   
       of your living relatives,

940
01:05:33,380 --> 01:05:35,046
also your parents
               and grandparents.

941
01:05:35,048 --> 01:05:36,747
Well, the documents             
that you will see--

942
01:05:36,749 --> 01:05:38,749
Can answer many questions,
             but not all.

943
01:05:38,751 --> 01:05:40,669
Oh, one more thing.

944
01:05:40,671 --> 01:05:42,570
It would be helpful   
       if you could accompany me

945
01:05:42,572 --> 01:05:44,339
on a visit 
                    to Augsburg.
     Augsburg?

946
01:05:44,341 --> 01:05:46,491
The ancestral home     
    of the de Bleuchamps family.

947
01:05:46,493 --> 01:05:49,327
There are notable Bleuchamps
       tombs in the cathedral

948
01:05:49,329 --> 01:05:51,646
and some important records
         in the city archives.

949
01:05:51,648 --> 01:05:54,282
If you were there to assist 
  with your personal knowledge--

950
01:05:54,284 --> 01:05:56,651
That may not be convenient      
for some time.

951
01:05:56,653 --> 01:05:58,987
But I'm determined that      
my title shall be recognized.

952
01:05:58,989 --> 01:06:01,773
In any event, you may proceed  
with your preliminary research.

953
01:06:01,775 --> 01:06:03,491
I shall be happy        
     to start straightaway.

954
01:06:09,232 --> 01:06:11,332
Thank you,                    
Herr Grunther.

955
01:06:18,191 --> 01:06:20,141
[♪♪♪]

956
01:06:30,403 --> 01:06:32,803
[♪♪♪]

957
01:07:36,053 --> 01:07:39,037
[BUNT SPEAKING IN GERMAN    
            OUTSIDE]

958
01:07:39,039 --> 01:07:41,205
[BUNT AND MAN CONVERSING    
           IN GERMAN]

959
01:07:55,405 --> 01:07:57,338
[♪♪♪]

960
01:08:18,995 --> 01:08:20,895
[♪♪♪]

961
01:08:20,897 --> 01:08:22,630
[CLICKS]

962
01:08:33,810 --> 01:08:35,143
Sir Hilary!

963
01:08:35,145 --> 01:08:36,428
Shh!

964
01:08:36,430 --> 01:08:38,830
[WHISPERING]                    
I brought you the book.

965
01:08:38,832 --> 01:08:39,831
The illustrated book?

966
01:08:39,833 --> 01:08:42,333
No, don't turn it on.

967
01:08:42,335 --> 01:08:43,435
I want to see the pictures.

968
01:08:43,437 --> 01:08:45,570
But you're a picture
                  yourself,

969
01:08:45,572 --> 01:08:47,322
and twice as lovely   
           in the firelight.

970
01:08:47,324 --> 01:08:51,492
You are funny,           
pretending not to like girls.

971
01:08:51,494 --> 01:08:53,028
Well, I don't, usually.

972
01:08:53,030 --> 01:08:55,696
But you're not usual.

973
01:08:55,698 --> 01:08:57,365
That lipstick   
             was an inspiration.

974
01:08:57,367 --> 01:08:58,833
So are you.

975
01:08:58,835 --> 01:09:01,336
Oh, Sir Hilary.

976
01:09:01,338 --> 01:09:04,039
Call me..."Hilly."

977
01:09:04,041 --> 01:09:05,639
Hilly.

978
01:09:07,177 --> 01:09:08,510
What's your name?

979
01:09:08,512 --> 01:09:10,795
Ruby Bartlett,             
    from Lancashire.

980
01:09:10,797 --> 01:09:12,029
Morecambe Bay, actually.

981
01:09:12,031 --> 01:09:13,431
How did you get here?

982
01:09:14,634 --> 01:09:17,435
Do we have                
to talk about that now?

983
01:09:33,436 --> 01:09:35,120
[RUBY GIGGLES]

984
01:09:35,122 --> 01:09:37,021
It's true!

985
01:09:43,346 --> 01:09:45,079
How did you get here?

986
01:09:46,616 --> 01:09:49,583
I had this awful allergy
             about chickens.

987
01:09:49,585 --> 01:09:51,452
My family's   
              got a chicken farm

988
01:09:51,454 --> 01:09:53,221
and every time       
    I had to do something on it,

989
01:09:53,223 --> 01:09:55,256
I nearly died.

990
01:09:55,258 --> 01:09:57,859
A specialist said there was
     this wonderful Swiss clinic

991
01:09:57,861 --> 01:09:59,426
where they cured you, free,

992
01:09:59,428 --> 01:10:01,495
because they were researching
         at the same time.

993
01:10:04,718 --> 01:10:05,883
Go on.

994
01:10:05,885 --> 01:10:07,184
No, about the clinic,           
       I mean.

995
01:10:07,186 --> 01:10:09,186
Oh.

996
01:10:09,188 --> 01:10:13,624
Well, the specialist had me 
   meet Fraülein Bunt in London,

997
01:10:13,626 --> 01:10:17,412
and she said I had   
        a very interesting case.

998
01:10:17,414 --> 01:10:19,514
How right she was.

999
01:10:19,516 --> 01:10:22,082
Oh, Hilly.

1000
01:10:22,084 --> 01:10:24,084
[HORN BLARES]          
                 Oh, bother!

1001
01:10:24,086 --> 01:10:26,153
No, Hilly!

1002
01:10:26,155 --> 01:10:28,222
It's part of the cure.

1003
01:10:34,431 --> 01:10:36,230
Cassette number seven.

1004
01:10:43,173 --> 01:10:44,672
Number eight.

1005
01:10:49,595 --> 01:10:52,496
BLOFELD [OVER SPEAKER]:     
        <i> Do you remember</i>        
   <i> when you first came here,</i>

1006
01:10:52,498 --> 01:10:54,966
<i> how you hated chickens?</i>

1007
01:10:54,968 --> 01:10:58,535
<i> How you were sick</i>       
    <i> when you even saw one?</i>

1008
01:10:58,537 --> 01:11:00,637
<i> But all that is over now.</i>

1009
01:11:00,639 --> 01:11:03,741
<i> For I have shown you</i>      
      <i> how foolish it was,</i>

1010
01:11:03,743 --> 01:11:06,610
<i> and your cure is nearly done.</i>

1011
01:11:06,612 --> 01:11:09,180
<i> I have taught you</i>       
       <i> to love chickens.</i>

1012
01:11:09,182 --> 01:11:12,984
<i> To love their flesh,</i>      
         <i> their voice.</i>

1013
01:11:12,986 --> 01:11:15,819
<i> Yes, your cure is nearly done.</i>

1014
01:11:15,821 --> 01:11:19,090
<i> And soon you will go home--</i>  
            Ruby?

1015
01:11:19,092 --> 01:11:21,092
<i> --to look after the chickens--</i> 
 Ruby, wake up!

1016
01:11:21,094 --> 01:11:23,394
<i> --which you love so much.</i>

1017
01:11:23,396 --> 01:11:25,562
You do love me just a little,
         don't you, Hilly?

1018
01:11:25,564 --> 01:11:27,015
<i> One more thing</i>         
        <i> before you go.</i>

1019
01:11:27,017 --> 01:11:28,316
Ruby.

1020
01:11:28,318 --> 01:11:32,086
<i> I must teach you</i>        
<i> how to give them special care.</i>

1021
01:11:33,306 --> 01:11:35,006
<i> I will tell you what to do.</i>

1022
01:11:35,008 --> 01:11:37,808
Ruby, wake up.         
     <i> I will tell you when.</i>

1023
01:11:37,810 --> 01:11:39,927
<i> I will tell you how.</i>

1024
01:11:41,280 --> 01:11:44,381
<i> And after you've done</i>     
       <i> what I teach you,</i>

1025
01:11:44,383 --> 01:11:47,217
<i> you will forget it forever.</i>

1026
01:11:47,219 --> 01:11:48,820
<i> Forever.</i>

1027
01:11:55,661 --> 01:11:57,261
[CLICKS]

1028
01:12:11,010 --> 01:12:14,646
Hilly, you old devil.

1029
01:12:14,648 --> 01:12:17,749
[♪♪♪]

1030
01:12:17,751 --> 01:12:19,984
It is me, yes?

1031
01:12:19,986 --> 01:12:21,669
Quite undeniably, yes.

1032
01:12:23,073 --> 01:12:24,572
BOND:              
      How did you get out?

1033
01:12:26,009 --> 01:12:27,808
With a fingernail file.

1034
01:12:27,810 --> 01:12:30,278
It's so easy.

1035
01:12:30,280 --> 01:12:32,046
I wouldn't know.

1036
01:12:34,884 --> 01:12:36,984
I come to see the book,
            the pictures, yes?

1037
01:12:36,986 --> 01:12:38,219
Oh, jolly good idea.

1038
01:12:38,221 --> 01:12:40,021
Now, where did I put it?

1039
01:12:41,390 --> 01:12:43,891
Hm, I had it                    
a few moments ago.

1040
01:12:43,893 --> 01:12:45,259
Perhaps if we turn on
                 the light?

1041
01:12:45,261 --> 01:12:46,961
No.

1042
01:12:46,963 --> 01:12:49,430
You're a picture yourself.

1043
01:12:49,432 --> 01:12:51,866
And twice as lovely
              in the firelight.

1044
01:12:51,868 --> 01:12:53,500
But, Sir Hilary...

1045
01:12:53,502 --> 01:12:54,802
Hilly.

1046
01:12:54,804 --> 01:12:57,705
But I think you do not          
  like girls, Hilly.

1047
01:12:57,707 --> 01:13:01,409
Usually, I don't.  
           But you're not usual.

1048
01:13:01,411 --> 01:13:03,878
Coming here like this
            was an inspiration.

1049
01:13:03,880 --> 01:13:05,680
So are you.

1050
01:13:05,682 --> 01:13:06,714
[MOANS]

1051
01:13:06,716 --> 01:13:07,832
You'll need to be.

1052
01:13:07,834 --> 01:13:09,233
What you say?

1053
01:13:09,235 --> 01:13:11,002
I said, a miracle,  
          our meeting like this.

1054
01:13:11,004 --> 01:13:13,404
I don't even know
                   your name.

1055
01:13:13,406 --> 01:13:16,641
I tell you                
all about myself later.

1056
01:13:18,444 --> 01:13:19,911
In the morning.

1057
01:13:24,100 --> 01:13:26,300
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

1058
01:13:59,668 --> 01:14:01,602
Hey.

1059
01:14:01,604 --> 01:14:03,270
What about a lift               
   to the top?

1060
01:14:03,272 --> 01:14:06,040
It is not permitted.
               All is private.

1061
01:14:06,042 --> 01:14:08,642
But surely there's a restaurant,
a sports club up there.

1062
01:14:08,644 --> 01:14:10,144
I've seen them                  
 advertised.

1063
01:14:10,146 --> 01:14:11,312
It's all closed now.

1064
01:14:11,314 --> 01:14:12,613
Since when?

1065
01:14:12,615 --> 01:14:14,281
I've seen them advertised,      
I tell you.

1066
01:14:14,283 --> 01:14:15,483
You are mistaken, sir.

1067
01:14:15,485 --> 01:14:17,351
For many weeks,         
       they are finished.

1068
01:14:17,353 --> 01:14:19,387
All right, but I'd still        
like to get to the top.

1069
01:14:19,389 --> 01:14:21,356
From here up,          
        it's forbidden!

1070
01:14:21,358 --> 01:14:23,825
Private! Closed!

1071
01:14:25,261 --> 01:14:26,394
All right.

1072
01:14:32,802 --> 01:14:34,501
[GRUNTS]

1073
01:14:49,969 --> 01:14:52,402
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

1074
01:14:54,073 --> 01:14:55,906
It's my turn now.

1075
01:14:58,377 --> 01:15:00,144
[ALL LAUGH]

1076
01:15:00,146 --> 01:15:01,229
Sir Hilary!

1077
01:15:01,231 --> 01:15:02,597
Good morning.

1078
01:15:02,599 --> 01:15:05,433
Good morning, Sir Hilary. 
    Your stiffness of last night

1079
01:15:05,435 --> 01:15:07,869
it is all gone?

1080
01:15:07,871 --> 01:15:09,103
For the time being,       
            I think.

1081
01:15:09,105 --> 01:15:11,205
Then come and do curling
          with us, Sir Hilary.

1082
01:15:11,207 --> 01:15:13,241
Won't that be frightfully    
           energetic?           
                             No.

1083
01:15:13,243 --> 01:15:14,542
We'll show you.

1084
01:15:14,544 --> 01:15:15,642
Perhaps you'd teach me.

1085
01:15:26,139 --> 01:15:28,071
[WOMEN CLAMORING]

1086
01:15:29,509 --> 01:15:30,608
Have a go.

1087
01:15:30,610 --> 01:15:32,009
We expect great things
                  of you.

1088
01:15:37,233 --> 01:15:39,900
We're leaving very soon, Hilly.
         I must see you.

1089
01:15:39,902 --> 01:15:41,402
Eight o'clock tonight.

1090
01:15:41,404 --> 01:15:42,569
[SQUAWKING]

1091
01:15:58,705 --> 01:16:00,404
And the man was alone?

1092
01:16:02,508 --> 01:16:05,209
Ah, good morning, ladies.

1093
01:16:05,211 --> 01:16:06,977
Good morning!

1094
01:16:06,979 --> 01:16:10,047
Good morning, Sir Hilary,       
and how's your research?

1095
01:16:10,049 --> 01:16:12,750
Riveting.            
    And very promising too.

1096
01:16:12,752 --> 01:16:15,520
MAN:              
   I've never heard anything    
 so ridiculous in all my life!

1097
01:16:15,522 --> 01:16:17,855
Since when is climbing     
 a mountain a criminal offence?

1098
01:16:17,857 --> 01:16:19,122
Excuse me.

1099
01:16:19,124 --> 01:16:22,026
Piz Gloria, sir,                
is private property.

1100
01:16:22,028 --> 01:16:23,394
The whole Alp?         
          Ridiculous!

1101
01:16:23,396 --> 01:16:27,031
There are many signs,  
      and my servant warned you.

1102
01:16:27,033 --> 01:16:29,500
Your throw,      
              I think it is.

1103
01:16:29,502 --> 01:16:31,335
Oh, no, I had my throw.

1104
01:16:31,337 --> 01:16:32,603
Made a mess of it,       
          I'm afraid.

1105
01:16:32,605 --> 01:16:34,939
That didn't count.  
           You can throw again.

1106
01:16:34,941 --> 01:16:35,940
Oh, yes, go on.

1107
01:16:35,942 --> 01:16:37,375
Very civil of you,       
           fraülein.

1108
01:16:37,377 --> 01:16:40,360
--doesn't entitle these goons  
    to start shooting at me.

1109
01:16:40,362 --> 01:16:41,695
Who the hell are you anyway?

1110
01:16:41,697 --> 01:16:43,564
I am the director
              of this institute.

1111
01:16:48,671 --> 01:16:50,204
You'll be sent down
                 by cable car

1112
01:16:50,206 --> 01:16:53,007
and you will refrain  
        from troubling us again!

1113
01:16:53,009 --> 01:16:54,141
What about my belongings?

1114
01:16:54,143 --> 01:16:55,676
BLOFELD:                
They will be sent later.

1115
01:16:55,678 --> 01:16:56,844
But they're mine,        
            damn it!

1116
01:16:56,846 --> 01:17:00,631
We have certain rules      
    which must be observed.

1117
01:17:02,652 --> 01:17:04,402
The authorities      
        will hear about this!

1118
01:17:04,404 --> 01:17:05,952
Good day, sir.

1119
01:17:10,510 --> 01:17:12,877
Director-- Or count, as I think
      I can now safely say.

1120
01:17:12,879 --> 01:17:14,144
Yes.

1121
01:17:14,146 --> 01:17:15,746
I thought I'd take
              the afternoon off,

1122
01:17:15,748 --> 01:17:17,548
so if you're sending
            the cable car down--

1123
01:17:17,550 --> 01:17:19,917
But you've already              
had the morning off, Sir Hilary.

1124
01:17:19,919 --> 01:17:21,869
Must have a bit
                  of fresh air.

1125
01:17:21,871 --> 01:17:23,571
Those ancestors    
         of yours are hard work.

1126
01:17:23,573 --> 01:17:25,590
And the College of Arms         
is being very well paid.

1127
01:17:25,592 --> 01:17:27,741
Well, if you put it   
              like that--

1128
01:17:27,743 --> 01:17:29,293
I do put it like that.

1129
01:17:29,295 --> 01:17:30,895
Let me show you  
             what I've achieved,

1130
01:17:30,897 --> 01:17:32,547
then we can plan  
           this trip to Augsburg

1131
01:17:32,549 --> 01:17:34,431
and finish it all off.
Not over Christmas.

1132
01:17:34,433 --> 01:17:36,300
The archives will be closed,    
       will they not?

1133
01:17:37,837 --> 01:17:41,522
Come, girls.          
   It's time for our massage.

1134
01:17:41,524 --> 01:17:45,026
Girls, that is enough
             curling for today.

1135
01:17:45,028 --> 01:17:47,094
[WOMEN GROANING]

1136
01:17:49,365 --> 01:17:50,931
I must see you tonight.

1137
01:17:50,933 --> 01:17:52,366
Nine o'clock?

1138
01:17:55,171 --> 01:17:58,172
Ten? Well, back to work.

1139
01:17:59,608 --> 01:18:01,909
You've no idea  
             how it's piling up.

1140
01:18:06,982 --> 01:18:09,783
[♪♪♪]

1141
01:18:20,563 --> 01:18:23,531
Ruby. It's me, Hilly.

1142
01:18:25,635 --> 01:18:28,068
Hilly's so sad   
            that Ruby's leaving.

1143
01:18:28,070 --> 01:18:29,703
[RUBY GIGGLES]

1144
01:18:29,705 --> 01:18:32,523
Has that old cow told you--?

1145
01:18:32,525 --> 01:18:34,007
Fancy meeting you here,     
           fraülein!

1146
01:18:54,930 --> 01:18:56,363
Merry Christmas, 007.

1147
01:18:57,516 --> 01:18:58,933
I'm Sir Hilary Bray.

1148
01:18:58,935 --> 01:19:01,535
[CHUCKLING]           
       No, no, Mr. Bond.

1149
01:19:01,537 --> 01:19:04,138
Respectable baronets      
  from the College of Heralds

1150
01:19:04,140 --> 01:19:06,807
do not seduce          
  female patients in clinics.

1151
01:19:06,809 --> 01:19:07,974
On the other hand,

1152
01:19:07,976 --> 01:19:10,945
they do get their               
professional details right.

1153
01:19:10,947 --> 01:19:12,313
The Bleuchamp tombs

1154
01:19:12,315 --> 01:19:14,614
are not in the         
Augsburg Cathedral, as you said,

1155
01:19:14,616 --> 01:19:18,552
but in the Saint Anna Kirche.  
Sir Hilary Bray would've known.

1156
01:19:19,755 --> 01:19:21,489
A small slip.

1157
01:19:21,491 --> 01:19:24,125
Takes more than a few props   
   to turn 007 into a herald.

1158
01:19:24,127 --> 01:19:26,527
Take more than cutting off   
    your earlobes, Blofeld,

1159
01:19:26,529 --> 01:19:27,828
to turn you into a count.

1160
01:19:27,830 --> 01:19:29,430
I may yet surprise you,

1161
01:19:29,432 --> 01:19:32,416
but I'm afraid that you have  
   no surprises left for me.

1162
01:19:32,418 --> 01:19:35,386
I know all about your mission,  
          Mr. Bond.

1163
01:19:35,388 --> 01:19:37,021
Your colleague.

1164
01:19:37,023 --> 01:19:38,789
Such a keen climber,

1165
01:19:38,791 --> 01:19:41,058
such a brilliant        
      conversationalist...

1166
01:19:41,060 --> 01:19:42,393
before he left us.

1167
01:19:42,395 --> 01:19:44,461
You realize           
    he reported where I am.

1168
01:19:44,463 --> 01:19:45,813
I doubt that.

1169
01:19:45,815 --> 01:19:48,232
In any case, no one's going   
    to come to your rescue.

1170
01:19:48,234 --> 01:19:50,867
In a few hours,         
       the United Nations

1171
01:19:50,869 --> 01:19:53,688
will receive          
     my yuletide greetings:

1172
01:19:53,690 --> 01:19:56,590
The information that I now   
  possess the scientific means

1173
01:19:56,592 --> 01:19:59,126
to control...or to destroy

1174
01:19:59,128 --> 01:20:01,595
the economy of the whole world.

1175
01:20:01,597 --> 01:20:04,714
People will have more important 
things to think about than you.

1176
01:20:04,716 --> 01:20:05,949
If they believe your threat.

1177
01:20:05,951 --> 01:20:08,085
[BLOFELD LAUGHS]

1178
01:20:08,087 --> 01:20:09,686
Oh, they will.

1179
01:20:09,688 --> 01:20:11,706
In any case,          
I have prepared a demonstration.

1180
01:20:11,708 --> 01:20:13,874
Remember that                   
disagreeable outbreak

1181
01:20:13,876 --> 01:20:17,611
of foot-and-mouth disease       
in England last summer?

1182
01:20:19,732 --> 01:20:23,601
Well, I shall instruct them,  
   in very convincing terms,

1183
01:20:23,603 --> 01:20:24,802
exactly how I arranged that.

1184
01:20:24,804 --> 01:20:28,505
And my capacity                 
has improved since.

1185
01:20:28,507 --> 01:20:29,673
Allergy vaccines?

1186
01:20:31,894 --> 01:20:33,611
Bacteria.

1187
01:20:33,613 --> 01:20:35,980
BOND:         
        Bacteriological warfare.

1188
01:20:35,982 --> 01:20:37,547
With a difference.

1189
01:20:37,549 --> 01:20:40,050
Our great breakthrough     
       since last summer

1190
01:20:40,052 --> 01:20:42,286
has been the confection     
          of a certain

1191
01:20:42,288 --> 01:20:44,521
Virus Omega.

1192
01:20:44,523 --> 01:20:45,790
Infertility.

1193
01:20:45,792 --> 01:20:48,659
Total infertility        
     in plants and animals.

1194
01:20:48,661 --> 01:20:51,395
Not just disease in a few herds,
           Mr. Bond,

1195
01:20:51,397 --> 01:20:53,264
or the loss of a single crop,

1196
01:20:53,266 --> 01:20:56,333
but the destruction       
  of a whole strain, forever,

1197
01:20:56,335 --> 01:20:58,169
throughout an entire continent.

1198
01:20:58,171 --> 01:20:59,937
If my demands are not met,

1199
01:20:59,939 --> 01:21:02,239
I shall proceed with      
   the systematic extinction

1200
01:21:02,241 --> 01:21:04,041
of whole species of cereals   
         and livestock

1201
01:21:04,043 --> 01:21:05,176
all over the world.

1202
01:21:05,178 --> 01:21:07,561
Including, I suppose,      
        the human race?

1203
01:21:07,563 --> 01:21:11,198
I don't think, do you, Mr. Bond,

1204
01:21:11,200 --> 01:21:13,534
the United Nations       
   will let it come to that.

1205
01:21:13,536 --> 01:21:16,320
Not after their scientists   
     analyze a small sample

1206
01:21:16,322 --> 01:21:18,755
of Virus Omega                
they have received.

1207
01:21:18,757 --> 01:21:20,324
Epidemics of sterility.

1208
01:21:20,326 --> 01:21:24,695
Nothing is born.       
  No seed even begins to sprout.

1209
01:21:24,697 --> 01:21:26,280
They'll find an antidote.

1210
01:21:26,282 --> 01:21:28,416
Of course!

1211
01:21:28,418 --> 01:21:30,384
If I give them enough time.

1212
01:21:30,386 --> 01:21:32,252
They'll have time.

1213
01:21:32,254 --> 01:21:33,554
Once they're warned,

1214
01:21:33,556 --> 01:21:35,489
you'll have a problem
           dispensing the stuff.

1215
01:21:35,491 --> 01:21:37,958
That problem              
has already been solved.

1216
01:21:37,960 --> 01:21:40,494
I have been training            
   my own special

1217
01:21:40,496 --> 01:21:41,979
"Angels of Death."

1218
01:21:41,981 --> 01:21:43,214
Those girls.

1219
01:21:43,216 --> 01:21:45,800
Those girls,             
and many others like them.

1220
01:21:45,802 --> 01:21:47,701
But exactly how?

1221
01:21:50,489 --> 01:21:52,006
That will remain my secret.

1222
01:21:53,692 --> 01:21:55,025
And how many hundred millions

1223
01:21:55,027 --> 01:21:57,561
do you want for your services  
      this time, Blofeld?

1224
01:21:57,563 --> 01:22:00,130
This time? This time,      
 the price is of another kind.

1225
01:22:00,132 --> 01:22:02,282
You'll be more amused      
      when you know what.

1226
01:22:02,284 --> 01:22:03,283
In the meanwhile,

1227
01:22:03,285 --> 01:22:04,735
I will keep you here            
    as my guest.

1228
01:22:04,737 --> 01:22:08,105
You'll be very useful in helping
  to convince the authorities

1229
01:22:08,107 --> 01:22:10,441
that I mean what I say...

1230
01:22:10,443 --> 01:22:13,076
and I'll do what I claim.

1231
01:22:13,078 --> 01:22:15,512
Come, let me show you      
     to your new quarters.

1232
01:22:18,967 --> 01:22:21,868
You're likely to be with us   
    for some time, Mr. Bond.

1233
01:22:21,870 --> 01:22:23,504
So first...

1234
01:22:23,506 --> 01:22:26,940
a little therapy to soothe
         your restless nature.

1235
01:22:28,260 --> 01:22:31,161
Oh, poor fellow.              
He was restless too.

1236
01:22:31,163 --> 01:22:34,265
You perverse British,      
  how you love your exercise.

1237
01:22:34,267 --> 01:22:37,368
Every year,             
dozens of amateur climbers--

1238
01:22:37,370 --> 01:22:39,353
They wind up              
in the same predicament.

1239
01:22:39,355 --> 01:22:42,439
A kind of waxworks show     
      for morbid tourists.

1240
01:22:42,441 --> 01:22:43,606
[CLICKS TONGUE]

1241
01:22:43,608 --> 01:22:44,825
Dear, dear me.

1242
01:22:44,827 --> 01:22:47,328
[♪♪♪]

1243
01:22:52,784 --> 01:22:55,285
Now, now.                  
Now, now, Mr. Bond.

1244
01:22:55,287 --> 01:22:57,620
You must learn               
to be absolutely calm

1245
01:22:57,622 --> 01:23:00,307
before we can accept you        
back into polite society.

1246
01:23:31,324 --> 01:23:34,424
[METAL CLANKS]

1247
01:23:34,426 --> 01:23:36,009
[DISTANT CLANKING]

1248
01:23:50,810 --> 01:23:52,042
Presents!

1249
01:23:52,044 --> 01:23:55,312
[WOMEN CHATTERING]

1250
01:23:55,314 --> 01:23:56,947
Going-away presents

1251
01:23:56,949 --> 01:24:00,383
from the count himself,         
in appreciation.

1252
01:24:00,385 --> 01:24:01,885
I want     
               to open mine now!

1253
01:24:01,887 --> 01:24:05,105
No. It is more fun              
to open them all together, yes?

1254
01:24:05,107 --> 01:24:07,708
Please sit down.                
We will wait for the others.

1255
01:24:07,710 --> 01:24:09,275
[WOMEN LAUGHING]

1256
01:24:09,277 --> 01:24:11,244
Look, look, look!

1257
01:24:54,240 --> 01:24:56,873
Eggnog on Christmas Eve.    
        Just like home!

1258
01:24:56,875 --> 01:24:59,076
It is a treat                   
for the going-away party.

1259
01:24:59,078 --> 01:25:01,144
Your very good health,     
           my dears.

1260
01:25:01,146 --> 01:25:02,379
WOMEN:             
        Cheers! Cheers!

1261
01:25:02,381 --> 01:25:05,449
It has been so nice to cure you.

1262
01:25:28,306 --> 01:25:29,355
[RIPS]

1263
01:25:30,492 --> 01:25:31,475
[RIPS]

1264
01:25:52,715 --> 01:25:56,934
It has something special in it 
for the Holy Night celebration.

1265
01:25:56,936 --> 01:25:59,286
[♪♪♪]

1266
01:26:04,944 --> 01:26:07,710
[♪♪♪]

1267
01:26:38,761 --> 01:26:41,527
BLOFELD [OVER SPEAKER]:     
     <i> And now you're going</i>      
         <i> on a journey.</i>

1268
01:26:41,529 --> 01:26:43,429
<i> A journey home.</i>

1269
01:26:44,566 --> 01:26:47,300
<i> But first you must rest</i>    
          <i> for awhile.</i>

1270
01:26:47,302 --> 01:26:50,237
<i> Rest.</i>             
             <i> Rest.</i>

1271
01:26:51,706 --> 01:26:53,339
<i> Rest.</i>

1272
01:27:03,536 --> 01:27:05,201
[♪♪♪]

1273
01:27:24,023 --> 01:27:26,689
[MOTOR WHIRRING]

1274
01:28:54,229 --> 01:28:56,179
[MEN SPEAKING
                     IN GERMAN]

1275
01:29:23,809 --> 01:29:26,993
BLOFELD [ON SPEAKER]:  
         <i> I will tell you when,</i> 
       <i> and I will tell you how,</i>

1276
01:29:26,995 --> 01:29:29,262
<i> but it must be our secret.</i>

1277
01:29:29,264 --> 01:29:32,015
<i> Yours and mine.</i>
                  <i> Our secret.</i>

1278
01:29:32,017 --> 01:29:34,935
<i> And after you've done</i>     
       <i> what I teach you,</i>

1279
01:29:34,937 --> 01:29:38,171
<i> will you forget it...</i>

1280
01:29:38,173 --> 01:29:40,206
<i> forever?</i>

1281
01:29:40,208 --> 01:29:43,143
<i> Forever.</i>            
           <i> Forever.</i>

1282
01:29:44,697 --> 01:29:47,831
<i> And now you may</i>        
     <i> open your eyes again.</i>

1283
01:29:47,833 --> 01:29:50,200
<i> Each of you has been given</i>   
          <i> a present,</i>

1284
01:29:50,202 --> 01:29:52,535
<i> such a prettily wrapped</i>    
           <i> present.</i>

1285
01:29:52,537 --> 01:29:55,822
<i> Now is the time to open them.</i> 
          <i> Open them.</i>

1286
01:30:01,396 --> 01:30:04,197
<i> You see, they're beautiful,</i>

1287
01:30:04,199 --> 01:30:07,067
<i> and you're longing to know</i>   
        <i> what is inside.</i>

1288
01:30:09,037 --> 01:30:11,421
<i> You may use anything</i>      
      <i> but the atomizer...</i>

1289
01:30:14,076 --> 01:30:17,126
<i> which you must never touch--</i>  
            <i> Never.</i>

1290
01:30:17,128 --> 01:30:19,079
<i> --until I tell you how</i>

1291
01:30:19,081 --> 01:30:21,264
<i> and where to use it.</i>

1292
01:30:21,266 --> 01:30:23,233
<i> Open the compact.</i>

1293
01:30:26,739 --> 01:30:29,072
<i> Adjust the volume control.</i>

1294
01:30:31,259 --> 01:30:34,027
BLOFELD [FROM COMPACT]:     
 <i> Every night at exactly 12:00,</i>

1295
01:30:34,029 --> 01:30:35,462
<i> you must be alone</i>

1296
01:30:35,464 --> 01:30:38,381
<i> so that you can switch on</i>   
         <i> that receiver</i>

1297
01:30:38,383 --> 01:30:40,684
<i> and listen for my voice.</i>

1298
01:30:40,686 --> 01:30:43,754
<i> I'll tell you what to do,</i>   
     <i> I will tell you when,</i>

1299
01:30:43,756 --> 01:30:45,922
<i> and I will tell you how.</i>

1300
01:30:45,924 --> 01:30:47,690
<i> After you've heard what I say</i>

1301
01:30:47,692 --> 01:30:50,710
<i> push the mirror back</i>      
<i> to conceal the receiver again.</i>

1302
01:30:50,712 --> 01:30:53,863
<i> Push it back now</i>        
      <i> and close the case.</i>

1303
01:30:59,671 --> 01:31:02,572
[ON SPEAKER]          
     <i> Now rest again. Rest.</i>

1304
01:31:03,842 --> 01:31:06,026
<i> Rest.</i>

1305
01:31:06,028 --> 01:31:09,496
<i> In a few minutes,</i>       
       <i> you will wake up.</i>

1306
01:31:09,498 --> 01:31:12,832
<i> You will not remember</i>     
     <i> what I just told you</i>

1307
01:31:12,834 --> 01:31:15,001
<i> until you return home.</i>

1308
01:31:16,238 --> 01:31:18,138
[ELEVATOR BELL CHIMES]

1309
01:31:24,112 --> 01:31:26,446
[INDISTINCT CHATTER             
    IN GERMAN]

1310
01:31:36,391 --> 01:31:37,991
[ELEVATOR BELL CHIMES]

1311
01:32:05,337 --> 01:32:07,187
[♪♪♪]

1312
01:32:08,524 --> 01:32:10,106
<i> Hilfe!</i>

1313
01:32:23,354 --> 01:32:25,272
[ELEVATOR BELL CHIMES]

1314
01:32:25,274 --> 01:32:27,574
[CHATTERING]

1315
01:32:27,576 --> 01:32:29,543
WOMAN 1:            
     What a lovely present.

1316
01:32:29,545 --> 01:32:31,661
WOMAN 2:            
     I don't feel too good.

1317
01:32:32,831 --> 01:32:35,565
Please, girls,  
              we are in a hurry.

1318
01:32:44,542 --> 01:32:46,142
[WHISPERS]             
      Merry Christmas.

1319
01:32:46,845 --> 01:32:48,928
[WOMEN CHATTERING]

1320
01:33:09,601 --> 01:33:12,569
Maybe you should've       
       been gift-wrapped.

1321
01:33:12,571 --> 01:33:15,004
[♪♪♪]

1322
01:33:35,894 --> 01:33:38,060
[SHOUTING IN GERMAN]

1323
01:33:50,025 --> 01:33:53,193
[SHOUTING IN GERMAN]

1324
01:33:53,195 --> 01:33:54,960
[PHONE RINGS]

1325
01:33:54,962 --> 01:33:56,696
[GUARD SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

1326
01:33:56,698 --> 01:33:57,747
[CAT GROWLS]

1327
01:33:57,749 --> 01:33:59,148
[SHOUTING IN GERMAN]

1328
01:35:20,082 --> 01:35:21,348
Flare.

1329
01:35:27,422 --> 01:35:29,272
GUARD:             
  He's making for the village.

1330
01:35:29,274 --> 01:35:30,840
We'll head him off   
           at the precipice.

1331
01:35:30,842 --> 01:35:32,575
[♪♪♪]

1332
01:36:27,849 --> 01:36:29,382
Idiot.

1333
01:36:59,614 --> 01:37:02,281
[FESTIVE MUSIC PLAYING
                IN VILLAGE]

1334
01:37:10,609 --> 01:37:12,475
Aaaggh!

1335
01:37:36,084 --> 01:37:37,683
<i> Hilfe!</i>

1336
01:37:44,342 --> 01:37:45,341
[GRUNTS]

1337
01:37:47,396 --> 01:37:48,878
[GASPING]

1338
01:37:52,434 --> 01:37:53,949
[GURGLING]

1339
01:38:13,705 --> 01:38:15,338
Aaagh!

1340
01:38:19,678 --> 01:38:22,278
[FESTIVE MUSIC CONTINUES    
            PLAYING]

1341
01:38:32,474 --> 01:38:34,974
[MAN SPEAKING IN GERMAN     
          ON SPEAKER]

1342
01:38:34,976 --> 01:38:35,975
Goodbye, girls.

1343
01:38:35,977 --> 01:38:37,861
Merry Christmas. 
             Merry Christmas.

1344
01:38:37,863 --> 01:38:39,462
And a happy New Year.

1345
01:38:39,464 --> 01:38:41,463
[SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

1346
01:38:41,465 --> 01:38:42,649
WOMAN 1:        
           <i> Auf Wiedersehen.</i>

1347
01:38:42,651 --> 01:38:44,517
<i> Auf Wiedersehen.</i>

1348
01:38:44,519 --> 01:38:45,501
WOMAN 2:         
               Goodbye!

1349
01:38:47,856 --> 01:38:50,023
[CAR HORN HONKING]

1350
01:38:51,325 --> 01:38:53,392
[SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

1351
01:38:58,383 --> 01:39:00,733
[CONTINUES HONKING]

1352
01:39:05,623 --> 01:39:06,756
Right in there. Quick!

1353
01:39:08,059 --> 01:39:09,258
[SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

1354
01:39:14,182 --> 01:39:15,397
[BELLS RING]

1355
01:39:44,212 --> 01:39:45,478
[GRUNTS]

1356
01:39:49,768 --> 01:39:51,100
Bye.

1357
01:39:51,102 --> 01:39:53,236
[FESTIVE MUSIC CONTINUES    
            PLAYING]

1358
01:39:54,356 --> 01:39:55,404
[SHOUTING IN GERMAN]

1359
01:40:14,209 --> 01:40:15,575
Come on.

1360
01:40:15,577 --> 01:40:17,043
[HORN HONKING]

1361
01:40:25,387 --> 01:40:27,170
[CONTINUES HONKING]

1362
01:40:27,172 --> 01:40:29,872
[CROWD APPLAUDS]

1363
01:40:45,190 --> 01:40:47,823
[ANNOUNCER ON LOUDSPEAKER    
      SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

1364
01:40:51,396 --> 01:40:54,463
[NINA'S "DO YOU KNOW HOW    
   CHRISTMAS TREES ARE GROWN"   
      PLAYING ON SPEAKERS]

1365
01:40:57,202 --> 01:41:01,821
<i> ♪ Friendship and kindness ♪</i>

1366
01:41:01,823 --> 01:41:04,807
<i> ♪ But most of all ♪</i>

1367
01:41:05,843 --> 01:41:09,312
<i> ♪ They need love ♪</i>

1368
01:41:12,567 --> 01:41:17,270
<i> ♪ Do you know how Santa</i>    
        <i> Gets around? ♪</i>

1369
01:41:17,272 --> 01:41:21,106
<i> ♪ He needs snowflakes</i>     
         <i> Snowflakes ♪</i>

1370
01:41:24,112 --> 01:41:26,579
[LAUGHING]

1371
01:41:27,915 --> 01:41:30,616
<i> ♪ Reindeer, even though</i>    
          <i> They try ♪</i>

1372
01:41:30,618 --> 01:41:33,102
<i> ♪ They need other things ♪</i>

1373
01:41:33,104 --> 01:41:35,605
<i> ♪ Once a year</i>         
      <i> They have to fly ♪</i>

1374
01:41:35,607 --> 01:41:38,340
<i> ♪ And they don't have wings ♪</i>

1375
01:41:38,342 --> 01:41:42,912
<i> ♪ Do you know how</i>              
<i> Santa gets around? ♪</i>

1376
01:41:42,914 --> 01:41:44,530
[LAUGHING]

1377
01:41:44,532 --> 01:41:48,401
<i> ♪ He needs snowflakes</i>          
<i> And reindeer ♪</i>

1378
01:41:48,403 --> 01:41:52,388
<i> ♪ Sunshine and raindrops ♪</i>

1379
01:41:53,425 --> 01:41:58,094
<i> ♪ Friendship and kindness ♪</i>

1380
01:41:58,096 --> 01:42:02,247
<i> ♪ But most of all ♪</i>

1381
01:42:02,249 --> 01:42:05,918
<i> ♪ He needs love ♪</i>

1382
01:42:05,920 --> 01:42:06,902
James.

1383
01:42:08,823 --> 01:42:11,324
<i> ♪ Do you know</i>         
<i> How Christmas cards are made? ♪</i>

1384
01:42:11,326 --> 01:42:13,059
Darling, you're in trouble.
             What is it?

1385
01:42:13,061 --> 01:42:14,627
There's people after me.

1386
01:42:14,629 --> 01:42:15,728
Can I help?

1387
01:42:15,730 --> 01:42:17,063
Have you got a car?

1388
01:42:17,065 --> 01:42:18,498
Outside.       
[EXPLOSION]

1389
01:42:20,868 --> 01:42:22,568
Let's get out of here.

1390
01:42:24,172 --> 01:42:26,839
[CROWD CHEERING]

1391
01:42:33,882 --> 01:42:34,997
Stay close to me, James.

1392
01:42:55,152 --> 01:42:56,285
Not far now.

1393
01:43:01,076 --> 01:43:02,758
Nearside door.

1394
01:43:17,258 --> 01:43:19,658
[FIREWORKS CONTINUE EXPLODING]

1395
01:43:24,015 --> 01:43:25,431
Maybe he didn't see me.

1396
01:43:25,433 --> 01:43:27,699
I wouldn't go  
               "Banco!" on that.

1397
01:43:27,701 --> 01:43:29,702
Giving up bad habits, eh?

1398
01:43:29,704 --> 01:43:30,937
James, where are we heading?

1399
01:43:30,939 --> 01:43:33,505
Nearest post office           
   to contact London.

1400
01:43:34,842 --> 01:43:36,159
I know, Feldkirch.

1401
01:43:36,161 --> 01:43:38,077
Why are they looking
                  for you?

1402
01:43:38,079 --> 01:43:39,812
I suspect they're trying        
      to kill me.

1403
01:43:41,749 --> 01:43:43,148
Drive on.

1404
01:43:48,439 --> 01:43:49,789
No sign of them yet.

1405
01:43:49,791 --> 01:43:52,875
Or of someone   
            saying, "Thank you."

1406
01:43:52,877 --> 01:43:54,377
Thank you, Tracy.

1407
01:43:54,379 --> 01:43:57,346
You've got sharp eyes         
    and beautiful...

1408
01:43:57,348 --> 01:44:00,516
earlobes. What were you doing   
     so near Piz Gloria?

1409
01:44:00,518 --> 01:44:03,252
Now I have      
         a new interest in life.

1410
01:44:03,254 --> 01:44:04,853
Winter sports, eh?              
 Very wholesome.

1411
01:44:04,855 --> 01:44:06,922
Just one winter sportsman,

1412
01:44:06,924 --> 01:44:08,991
and Papa told me 
              where to find him.

1413
01:44:11,379 --> 01:44:13,279
[CAR HORN HONKING]

1414
01:44:13,281 --> 01:44:15,681
Just keep my mind             
  on your driving.

1415
01:44:16,568 --> 01:44:19,068
[CHURCH BELL RINGING]

1416
01:44:19,070 --> 01:44:21,537
Good. There it is, James.

1417
01:44:21,539 --> 01:44:22,671
Hurry.

1418
01:44:39,674 --> 01:44:41,307
[♪♪♪]

1419
01:44:42,276 --> 01:44:43,259
[GUNFIRE]

1420
01:44:43,261 --> 01:44:44,760
James!

1421
01:44:46,163 --> 01:44:48,930
[GUNFIRE CONTINUES]

1422
01:44:58,559 --> 01:45:00,359
[TIRES SCREECHING]

1423
01:45:06,835 --> 01:45:09,068
[TIRES SCREECHING]

1424
01:45:09,754 --> 01:45:10,886
Shoot at them!

1425
01:45:13,024 --> 01:45:14,173
Good girl.

1426
01:45:37,732 --> 01:45:39,748
[TIRES SCREECHING]

1427
01:45:40,368 --> 01:45:41,601
[GUNSHOTS]

1428
01:45:49,794 --> 01:45:50,976
Keep straight.

1429
01:45:56,084 --> 01:45:58,050
Turn left. That crowd         
  might discourage them.

1430
01:45:58,052 --> 01:46:00,286
[TIRES SCREECHING]

1431
01:46:02,390 --> 01:46:04,272
[CAR HORN HONKING]

1432
01:46:10,314 --> 01:46:12,198
[BOTH SCREAM]

1433
01:46:20,692 --> 01:46:22,491
[TIRES SCREECHING]       
      [CAR HORNS HONKING]

1434
01:46:22,493 --> 01:46:24,059
Looks like we've hit      
         the rush hour.

1435
01:46:25,330 --> 01:46:27,296
[CROWD SCREAMING]

1436
01:46:38,409 --> 01:46:39,408
We must stop them!

1437
01:46:41,812 --> 01:46:42,861
How do we get out?

1438
01:46:53,942 --> 01:46:55,908
BUNT:              
   Knock him out of the way!

1439
01:47:05,269 --> 01:47:07,452
I hope my big end  
          will stand up to this.

1440
01:47:12,243 --> 01:47:13,408
[METAL SCRAPING]

1441
01:47:36,801 --> 01:47:38,650
James! How do we get out?

1442
01:47:46,293 --> 01:47:48,010
Keep straight!

1443
01:48:02,376 --> 01:48:03,625
We can get out there.

1444
01:48:03,627 --> 01:48:05,393
TRACY: If you say so.           
       [CAR HORN HONKING]

1445
01:48:05,395 --> 01:48:06,628
[TIRES SQUEALING]

1446
01:48:06,630 --> 01:48:08,329
[SIRENS BLARING]

1447
01:48:10,551 --> 01:48:11,867
[SCREAMS]

1448
01:48:13,937 --> 01:48:15,821
[SHOUTS        
                IN GERMAN]

1449
01:48:17,741 --> 01:48:18,841
[CHUCKLES]

1450
01:48:18,843 --> 01:48:21,009
We didn't even stop             
  for the prize.

1451
01:48:22,096 --> 01:48:24,463
I told you that crowd           
would discourage them.

1452
01:48:28,235 --> 01:48:29,534
[WIND HOWLING]

1453
01:48:44,484 --> 01:48:46,535
Oh, that's all                  
we need right now.

1454
01:48:58,081 --> 01:48:59,397
Pull in there.

1455
01:49:10,744 --> 01:49:12,944
Keep moving.          
      I'll open the doors.

1456
01:49:30,114 --> 01:49:31,229
[HORSES SNORTING]

1457
01:49:32,216 --> 01:49:33,682
Sorry about    
             the accommodations,

1458
01:49:33,684 --> 01:49:34,750
contessa.

1459
01:49:34,752 --> 01:49:36,952
We should have              
rung ahead and booked.

1460
01:49:38,355 --> 01:49:40,188
If only I'd got through
                to London.

1461
01:49:40,190 --> 01:49:42,558
At least you'll               
get another chance.             
                      But when?

1462
01:49:42,560 --> 01:49:44,126
[LOUD BANGING]

1463
01:49:52,102 --> 01:49:54,887
[♪♪♪]

1464
01:50:04,198 --> 01:50:05,330
Let's get some rest.

1465
01:50:05,332 --> 01:50:07,582
We'll push on  
              as soon as we can.

1466
01:50:07,584 --> 01:50:09,418
At least it's dry.

1467
01:50:12,155 --> 01:50:15,090
[WIND HOWLING]

1468
01:50:15,092 --> 01:50:16,758
[HINGES SQUEAKING]

1469
01:50:16,760 --> 01:50:19,928
[♪♪♪]

1470
01:50:35,479 --> 01:50:38,379
What really went on             
 up there, James?

1471
01:50:38,381 --> 01:50:39,581
[CHUCKLES]

1472
01:50:39,583 --> 01:50:42,517
Her Majesty's Secret Service  
        is still my job.

1473
01:50:44,387 --> 01:50:46,554
But there isn't anything        
you can do about your job

1474
01:50:46,556 --> 01:50:48,123
at the moment, is there?

1475
01:50:48,125 --> 01:50:49,858
No.

1476
01:50:55,449 --> 01:50:58,633
Then why are you             
thinking about it now?

1477
01:50:59,670 --> 01:51:01,269
I'm not.

1478
01:51:05,593 --> 01:51:08,026
I'm thinking about us.

1479
01:51:13,000 --> 01:51:15,801
Tracy, an agent...

1480
01:51:15,803 --> 01:51:18,119
shouldn't be concerned  
      with anything but himself.

1481
01:51:21,224 --> 01:51:23,458
I understand.

1482
01:51:23,460 --> 01:51:25,277
We'll just have to go on        
    the way we are.

1483
01:51:25,279 --> 01:51:26,811
No.

1484
01:51:28,782 --> 01:51:30,715
I'll have to find     
        something else to do.

1485
01:51:33,887 --> 01:51:35,921
Are you sure, James?

1486
01:51:38,224 --> 01:51:39,307
I love you.

1487
01:51:40,910 --> 01:51:44,429
I know I'll never find
          another girl like you.

1488
01:51:47,200 --> 01:51:48,600
Will you marry me?

1489
01:51:59,780 --> 01:52:01,913
Do you mean it?

1490
01:52:01,915 --> 01:52:03,365
I mean it.

1491
01:52:16,563 --> 01:52:20,499
Mr. and Mrs. James Bond.

1492
01:52:20,501 --> 01:52:24,068
Of Acacia Avenue,            
   Tunbridge Wells.

1493
01:52:24,070 --> 01:52:26,638
Mmm. How about    
             Belgrave Square?

1494
01:52:26,640 --> 01:52:29,140
Or the Via Veneto, Rome.

1495
01:52:29,142 --> 01:52:32,243
Paris, convenient
                for Le Touquet.

1496
01:52:32,245 --> 01:52:35,246
Monaco, handy for the Rainiers.

1497
01:52:37,718 --> 01:52:40,685
I wonder how much      
  they're asking for this place.

1498
01:52:40,687 --> 01:52:42,286
[CHUCKLES]

1499
01:52:44,875 --> 01:52:47,525
The proper time for this
          is our wedding night.

1500
01:52:48,746 --> 01:52:51,546
And that's       
       my New Year's resolution.

1501
01:52:51,548 --> 01:52:52,714
Whatever you say, darling.

1502
01:52:52,716 --> 01:52:54,566
And that...is yours.

1503
01:53:00,607 --> 01:53:02,073
Good night, Tracy.

1504
01:53:03,843 --> 01:53:05,543
Good night, James.

1505
01:53:23,797 --> 01:53:24,963
It's not New Year yet.

1506
01:53:24,965 --> 01:53:26,231
[CHUCKLES]

1507
01:53:29,653 --> 01:53:30,918
[SNORTING SOFTLY]

1508
01:53:53,427 --> 01:53:56,628
[♪♪♪]

1509
01:54:04,688 --> 01:54:07,422
[♪♪♪]

1510
01:54:17,433 --> 01:54:18,683
James!             
                Keep going!

1511
01:54:57,124 --> 01:54:58,457
Simple!

1512
01:54:58,459 --> 01:54:59,874
Good girl.

1513
01:55:00,627 --> 01:55:01,626
[GUNFIRE]

1514
01:55:01,628 --> 01:55:02,927
[MAN SHOUTING IN GERMAN]

1515
01:55:22,349 --> 01:55:23,581
[SCREAMS]

1516
01:55:26,686 --> 01:55:30,388
[♪♪♪]

1517
01:55:34,578 --> 01:55:35,743
He had lots of guts.

1518
01:55:44,754 --> 01:55:46,487
You three     
                 keep going.

1519
01:56:29,833 --> 01:56:30,931
Let's head for the trees!

1520
01:57:04,418 --> 01:57:05,399
James!

1521
01:57:05,401 --> 01:57:06,901
Keep going!

1522
01:57:10,624 --> 01:57:11,839
[TRACY SCREAMS]

1523
01:57:12,792 --> 01:57:14,926
Tracy, cling onto me!

1524
01:57:33,730 --> 01:57:36,865
[WIND HOWLING]

1525
01:57:57,971 --> 01:58:02,907
[♪♪♪]

1526
01:58:05,228 --> 01:58:07,561
BLOFELD:            
 A grave deep enough, I think,

1527
01:58:07,563 --> 01:58:10,048
to prevent even 007       
         from walking.

1528
01:58:14,021 --> 01:58:15,553
Get the girl.

1529
01:58:37,877 --> 01:58:42,914
[♪♪♪]

1530
01:58:42,916 --> 01:58:44,382
[INTERCOM BUZZES]

1531
01:58:44,384 --> 01:58:47,101
MONEYPENNY:           
     <i> United Nations, sir.</i>      
        <i> Red scrambler.</i>

1532
01:58:48,104 --> 01:58:49,370
M here.

1533
01:58:53,876 --> 01:58:56,377
Yes, we're standing by          
as instructed.

1534
01:58:58,481 --> 01:59:00,080
I understand.

1535
01:59:02,686 --> 01:59:05,019
Thank you, sir.

1536
01:59:05,021 --> 01:59:07,121
Well, no decision               
has been announced yet.

1537
01:59:07,123 --> 01:59:09,324
Of course, it's                 
a total news blackout.

1538
01:59:09,326 --> 01:59:12,393
But my informant                
was very plain.

1539
01:59:12,395 --> 01:59:13,695
How plain, sir?

1540
01:59:13,697 --> 01:59:15,714
They're going to buy            
Blofeld off.

1541
01:59:18,118 --> 01:59:20,551
Sit down.

1542
01:59:20,553 --> 01:59:21,786
And the price?

1543
01:59:21,788 --> 01:59:23,554
Amnesty.

1544
01:59:23,556 --> 01:59:26,057
A full pardon                   
for all past crimes.

1545
01:59:26,059 --> 01:59:27,225
Official recognition

1546
01:59:27,227 --> 01:59:30,962
of his title when he retires    
     into private life

1547
01:59:30,964 --> 01:59:32,931
as Count de Bleuchamp.

1548
01:59:34,234 --> 01:59:37,001
He seems to set               
great store by that.

1549
01:59:38,238 --> 01:59:40,071
A very curious thing,           
      snobbery.

1550
01:59:40,073 --> 01:59:41,673
When will they conclude     
           the deal?

1551
01:59:41,675 --> 01:59:42,741
Blofeld wants to know

1552
01:59:42,743 --> 01:59:43,908
the council's decision

1553
01:59:43,910 --> 01:59:46,161
not later than midnight     
    the day after tomorrow.

1554
01:59:46,163 --> 01:59:48,413
Sir, that gives us time     
  to get to Piz Gloria first.

1555
01:59:48,415 --> 01:59:50,281
In force.
          No, 007.

1556
01:59:50,283 --> 01:59:51,949
My instructions                 
are quite clear.

1557
01:59:51,951 --> 01:59:53,550
But, sir,            
     destroy the institute

1558
01:59:53,552 --> 01:59:55,336
and destroy Blofeld       
     and his virus with it.

1559
01:59:55,338 --> 01:59:56,921
It's been rejected as too risky.

1560
01:59:56,923 --> 01:59:58,989
Those girls...

1561
02:00:00,260 --> 02:00:01,543
God knows how many,

1562
02:00:01,545 --> 02:00:03,011
let alone where.

1563
02:00:03,013 --> 02:00:05,446
Sir, if we destroy    
     the center of communication

1564
02:00:05,448 --> 02:00:06,648
that controls those girls,

1565
02:00:06,650 --> 02:00:08,849
without Blofeld's voice,
          they can do nothing.

1566
02:00:08,851 --> 02:00:10,051
I have my orders,

1567
02:00:10,053 --> 02:00:11,686
007, you have yours.            
Forget it.

1568
02:00:11,688 --> 02:00:13,521
And the girl          
     who helped me escape,

1569
02:00:13,523 --> 02:00:14,939
we just leave her there?

1570
02:00:14,941 --> 02:00:19,360
This department is not concerned
  with your personal problems.

1571
02:00:19,362 --> 02:00:22,529
This department owes her a debt.

1572
02:00:22,531 --> 02:00:23,615
She saved my life.

1573
02:00:23,617 --> 02:00:25,282
Operation Bedlam is dead.

1574
02:00:26,787 --> 02:00:28,236
Do you understand?

1575
02:00:28,238 --> 02:00:30,003
Yes, sir.

1576
02:00:30,005 --> 02:00:32,123
I understand.

1577
02:00:32,125 --> 02:00:33,691
[RINGS]

1578
02:00:33,693 --> 02:00:35,392
OPERATOR:            
 <i> Your call to Marc Ange Draco,</i>

1579
02:00:35,394 --> 02:00:36,928
<i> head of Draco Construction.</i>

1580
02:00:36,930 --> 02:00:38,630
Hello, Draco?               
        <i> Yes, who is it?</i>

1581
02:00:38,632 --> 02:00:40,832
Bond. James Bond.             
       <i> Thank God, James.</i>

1582
02:00:40,834 --> 02:00:42,934
I'd like to interest you        
  in a demolition deal

1583
02:00:42,936 --> 02:00:44,636
that requires              
certain aerial activity

1584
02:00:44,638 --> 02:00:45,619
to install equipment.

1585
02:00:52,429 --> 02:00:55,863
Are you sure we're going to find
  Teresa when we get up there?

1586
02:00:55,865 --> 02:00:58,032
I'm pretty certain.           
Even if she's not there,

1587
02:00:58,034 --> 02:01:00,100
there's a good reason           
  for going anyway.

1588
02:01:00,102 --> 02:01:02,020
So you've explained.
              Quite a crusade.

1589
02:01:02,022 --> 02:01:05,940
[♪♪♪]

1590
02:01:05,942 --> 02:01:09,009
It is a time                    
for celebration.

1591
02:01:09,011 --> 02:01:10,545
Perhaps,

1592
02:01:10,547 --> 02:01:12,279
if they agree.

1593
02:01:12,281 --> 02:01:14,114
They can do nothing else
            and you know it,

1594
02:01:14,116 --> 02:01:16,951
and they know it.

1595
02:01:16,953 --> 02:01:18,853
I shall be able      
            to offer you

1596
02:01:18,855 --> 02:01:22,289
anything your heart  
             could wish for.

1597
02:01:22,291 --> 02:01:24,158
Paid for with how many lives?

1598
02:01:24,160 --> 02:01:28,896
Oh, come now, Tracy,            
 don't be so proud.

1599
02:01:28,898 --> 02:01:32,567
Your own father's profession   
is not entirely within the law.

1600
02:01:32,569 --> 02:01:35,970
His brotherhood             
also have...exotic ways

1601
02:01:35,972 --> 02:01:37,104
to keep it a closed shop.

1602
02:01:39,009 --> 02:01:42,626
RADIO OPERATOR:         
    <i> Basel approach calling</i>     
    <i> unidentified aircraft.</i>

1603
02:01:42,628 --> 02:01:45,029
<i> You're flying</i>         
    <i> in controlled airspace.</i>

1604
02:01:45,031 --> 02:01:46,830
<i> We have no flight plan</i>     
         <i> filed on you.</i>

1605
02:01:46,832 --> 02:01:48,232
[OPERATOR CONTINUES SPEAKING]

1606
02:01:48,234 --> 02:01:51,669
I think some people don't know
         we're crusaders.

1607
02:01:53,372 --> 02:01:57,175
Now, if you're very,          
    very nice to me,

1608
02:01:57,177 --> 02:02:00,111
I could make you            
      my countess.

1609
02:02:00,113 --> 02:02:02,814
But I'm already
                   a countess.

1610
02:02:02,816 --> 02:02:04,082
Whereas if you           
       displease me,

1611
02:02:04,084 --> 02:02:06,784
I can promise you            
a very different estate.

1612
02:02:06,786 --> 02:02:08,786
Excuse me,                      
sir.                            
             Yes?

1613
02:02:08,788 --> 02:02:10,138
There is something              
on the radio

1614
02:02:10,140 --> 02:02:11,839
you should hear.

1615
02:02:11,841 --> 02:02:13,140
<i> ...and destination. Over.</i>

1616
02:02:13,142 --> 02:02:14,308
Excuse me.

1617
02:02:14,310 --> 02:02:16,094
CONTROLLER:           
  <i> This is Zurich information</i>

1618
02:02:16,096 --> 02:02:18,363
<i> calling unidentified aircraft.</i> 
             <i> Over.</i>

1619
02:02:18,365 --> 02:02:20,148
<i> I repeat:</i>           
  <i> This is Zurich information</i>

1620
02:02:20,150 --> 02:02:22,150
<i> calling unidentified aircraft.</i>

1621
02:02:22,152 --> 02:02:23,584
Well?           
                 That helicopter

1622
02:02:23,586 --> 02:02:24,685
is one of three.

1623
02:02:24,687 --> 02:02:26,404
None of them have answered
             air control.

1624
02:02:26,406 --> 02:02:27,505
And?

1625
02:02:27,507 --> 02:02:29,524
There are suspect aircraft      
in the vicinity.

1626
02:02:29,526 --> 02:02:33,160
CONTROLLER:           
        <i> ...pilot's name</i>        
    <i> and destination. Over.</i>

1627
02:02:33,162 --> 02:02:35,296
Zurich, this is Foxtrot,
              Gulf, Sierra,

1628
02:02:35,298 --> 02:02:37,332
leading Red Cross
              helicopter flight,

1629
02:02:37,334 --> 02:02:40,368
<i> carrying Red Cross</i>    
     <i> medical supplies to Italy.</i>

1630
02:02:40,370 --> 02:02:42,069
<i> What's the trouble?</i>
                   <i> Over.</i>

1631
02:02:42,071 --> 02:02:43,904
<i> We have no record</i>              
<i> of your flight plan</i>

1632
02:02:43,906 --> 02:02:44,923
<i> or registration.</i>

1633
02:02:44,925 --> 02:02:46,157
<i> Over.</i>

1634
02:02:49,262 --> 02:02:51,529
<i> I repeat, we have no record</i>    
<i> of your flight plan</i>

1635
02:02:51,531 --> 02:02:53,264
<i> or your registration. Over.</i>

1636
02:02:53,266 --> 02:02:54,465
Then your registrations

1637
02:02:54,467 --> 02:02:57,001
<i> must be out-of-date. Over.</i>

1638
02:02:57,003 --> 02:02:59,653
<i> Foxtrot, Gulf, Sierra,</i>         
<i> this is Zurich information.</i>

1639
02:02:59,655 --> 02:03:01,789
<i> You must land at Zurich</i>        
<i> and report.</i>

1640
02:03:01,791 --> 02:03:04,142
<i> I say again,</i>                   
<i> land at Zurich and report.</i>

1641
02:03:04,144 --> 02:03:05,409
<i> Over.</i>

1642
02:03:05,411 --> 02:03:07,445
Do you wish to commit murder?

1643
02:03:07,447 --> 02:03:09,781
I told you,     
          this is a mercy flight

1644
02:03:09,783 --> 02:03:13,284
<i> carrying blood plasma</i> 
        <i> and emergency equipment</i>

1645
02:03:13,286 --> 02:03:16,571
<i> for the victims</i>       
  <i> of the Italian flood disaster</i>

1646
02:03:16,573 --> 02:03:18,806
<i> at Rovigo.</i>

1647
02:03:18,808 --> 02:03:20,241
<i> I repeat:</i>

1648
02:03:20,243 --> 02:03:22,409
mercy flight.

1649
02:03:22,411 --> 02:03:23,661
You understand me?

1650
02:03:23,663 --> 02:03:24,662
[CLINKING]

1651
02:03:24,664 --> 02:03:26,397
<i> Gulf, Sierra?</i>                  
                           <i> Yes?</i>

1652
02:03:26,399 --> 02:03:29,467
<i> Zurich. Very well,</i>             
<i> you may proceed. Out.</i>

1653
02:03:29,469 --> 02:03:31,586
You see?       
              It is nothing.

1654
02:03:31,588 --> 02:03:32,970
That seems to have settled it.

1655
02:03:32,972 --> 02:03:35,840
In case one or both of us    
  is delayed on the way home,

1656
02:03:35,842 --> 02:03:38,443
it's better to have  
         a rendezvous for later.

1657
02:03:38,445 --> 02:03:40,178
Before we start         
      getting sentimental,

1658
02:03:40,180 --> 02:03:42,347
I think we're being followed.

1659
02:03:42,349 --> 02:03:45,683
I've been thinking            
about your proposition.

1660
02:03:47,320 --> 02:03:48,820
Please,

1661
02:03:48,822 --> 02:03:50,271
tell me more.

1662
02:03:50,273 --> 02:03:52,006
MAN:              
 <i> This is military air control.</i>

1663
02:03:52,008 --> 02:03:53,808
<i> There is no record</i>       
       <i> of your mission.</i>

1664
02:03:53,810 --> 02:03:55,910
<i> Alter course to Zurich</i>     
           <i> and land.</i>

1665
02:03:55,912 --> 02:03:58,612
<i> Fighters have been dispatched</i> 
    <i> to intercept you. Over.</i>

1666
02:03:58,614 --> 02:04:02,449
I suggest you check
             your records again,

1667
02:04:02,451 --> 02:04:04,118
carefully. Over.

1668
02:04:04,120 --> 02:04:06,954
<i> I repeat, return to Zurich</i>   
        <i> and land. Over.</i>

1669
02:04:06,956 --> 02:04:08,355
Check with Geneva.

1670
02:04:08,357 --> 02:04:11,826
Check with the Red Cross      
         in Geneva.

1671
02:04:11,828 --> 02:04:14,294
Meanwhile, call off         
      your air force.

1672
02:04:14,296 --> 02:04:16,363
It is making            
    my passengers sick.

1673
02:04:16,365 --> 02:04:18,049
<i> Foxtrot, Gulf, Sierra,</i>

1674
02:04:18,051 --> 02:04:19,983
<i> you are carrying passengers?</i>

1675
02:04:19,985 --> 02:04:22,520
Of course I am.

1676
02:04:22,522 --> 02:04:27,224
Distinguished representatives  
      of the world press.

1677
02:04:27,226 --> 02:04:29,160
They've had enough       
       of your nonsense.

1678
02:04:29,162 --> 02:04:30,311
So have I.

1679
02:04:30,313 --> 02:04:31,813
<i> Over and out.</i>

1680
02:04:36,870 --> 02:04:38,836
There's a lot more     
              to tell,

1681
02:04:38,838 --> 02:04:41,805
but there will be plenty
             of time later.

1682
02:04:41,807 --> 02:04:43,474
Take me                   
to the Alpine room.

1683
02:04:43,476 --> 02:04:46,143
Oh? Are you unhappy here?

1684
02:04:46,145 --> 02:04:47,544
[SIGHS]                   
        Oh.

1685
02:04:47,546 --> 02:04:49,380
I want to see                   
  the dawn.

1686
02:04:49,382 --> 02:04:50,614
Oh.

1687
02:04:50,616 --> 02:04:53,918
So poetic a pleasure.

1688
02:04:53,920 --> 02:04:55,670
What were      
          all the world's charms

1689
02:04:55,672 --> 02:04:57,371
to mighty Paris

1690
02:04:57,373 --> 02:05:01,308
when he found that first dawn   
  in the arms of his Helen?

1691
02:05:02,879 --> 02:05:04,312
And when do you expect
                the signal

1692
02:05:04,314 --> 02:05:06,113
accepting your terms?

1693
02:05:06,115 --> 02:05:10,784
Ah. Any time              
before midnight tonight.

1694
02:05:10,786 --> 02:05:14,621
Thy dawn, O master  
         of the world, thy dawn.

1695
02:05:14,623 --> 02:05:17,624
For thee, the sunlight          
creeps across the lawn.

1696
02:05:17,626 --> 02:05:18,826
For thee,                     
  the ships

1697
02:05:18,828 --> 02:05:20,578
are drawn down to the waves.

1698
02:05:20,580 --> 02:05:25,450
For thee, the markets throng    
    with myriad slaves.

1699
02:05:25,452 --> 02:05:29,136
For thee, the hammer        
    on the anvil rings.

1700
02:05:29,138 --> 02:05:31,071
For thee,

1701
02:05:31,073 --> 02:05:33,875
the poet                  
of beguilement sings.

1702
02:05:40,633 --> 02:05:42,383
Helicopters!    
           We're being attacked!

1703
02:05:42,385 --> 02:05:43,618
Get all positions covered!

1704
02:05:43,620 --> 02:05:46,387
[♪♪♪]

1705
02:05:46,389 --> 02:05:48,606
[EXPLOSION]

1706
02:05:48,608 --> 02:05:50,591
[GUNFIRE]

1707
02:05:58,017 --> 02:05:59,767
[SCREAMS]

1708
02:06:05,742 --> 02:06:07,108
[BULLETS RICOCHETING]

1709
02:06:15,835 --> 02:06:17,551
[MEN SHOUTING IN GERMAN]

1710
02:06:19,088 --> 02:06:20,554
Look to the girl!

1711
02:06:35,605 --> 02:06:37,438
[♪♪♪]

1712
02:06:37,440 --> 02:06:39,573
[GUNFIRE]

1713
02:07:06,186 --> 02:07:07,467
[GRUNTING]

1714
02:07:19,649 --> 02:07:21,164
[GUNFIRE]

1715
02:07:57,654 --> 02:07:58,786
[DISTANT EXPLOSIONS]

1716
02:08:01,057 --> 02:08:02,056
[TRACY YELLS]

1717
02:08:10,917 --> 02:08:12,066
[MEN SHOUTING, GUNFIRE]

1718
02:08:23,612 --> 02:08:25,045
Tracy! Darling.

1719
02:08:25,047 --> 02:08:26,480
Thank God, Teresa!
                       [GUNSHOT]

1720
02:08:27,133 --> 02:08:28,698
James, wait!

1721
02:08:29,686 --> 02:08:31,135
DRACO:       
           Guns make me nervous.

1722
02:08:31,137 --> 02:08:32,737
You've done your share.

1723
02:08:32,739 --> 02:08:34,271
Get her to safety.

1724
02:08:39,779 --> 02:08:40,945
Come on! Let's go!

1725
02:08:41,881 --> 02:08:43,364
And you!

1726
02:08:43,366 --> 02:08:46,066
Get the circuit                 
set up now! Let's go!

1727
02:08:49,789 --> 02:08:51,504
[SCREAMING]

1728
02:08:52,659 --> 02:08:54,125
[FIRES GUN]

1729
02:09:10,009 --> 02:09:12,676
[♪♪♪]

1730
02:09:23,656 --> 02:09:25,156
[GUNFIRE IN DISTANCE]

1731
02:09:25,158 --> 02:09:26,156
All points covered?

1732
02:09:26,158 --> 02:09:27,874
Yes, sir.                      
DRACO: Okay.

1733
02:09:51,517 --> 02:09:53,601
[♪♪♪]

1734
02:10:25,918 --> 02:10:27,083
All set to blow?

1735
02:10:27,085 --> 02:10:29,086
The fuse is set                 
for exactly five minutes

1736
02:10:29,088 --> 02:10:30,721
and 10 seconds time.

1737
02:10:30,723 --> 02:10:32,189
The place will                
be sealed forever.

1738
02:10:32,191 --> 02:10:33,691
Will that give         
      the Englishman time

1739
02:10:33,693 --> 02:10:35,259
to get out?

1740
02:10:35,261 --> 02:10:37,044
He knows the schedule.

1741
02:10:43,569 --> 02:10:44,685
[CLICKS]

1742
02:10:48,607 --> 02:10:50,607
Where are you going?         
            Papa, where's James?

1743
02:10:50,609 --> 02:10:52,109
Don't worry.              
  He'll join us soon.

1744
02:10:52,111 --> 02:10:54,611
But we can't leave him!     
      He doesn't need your help!

1745
02:10:54,613 --> 02:10:57,181
I will not go                  
 without him!                   
                You'll have to!

1746
02:10:58,984 --> 02:11:01,751
Spare the rod and spoil
              the child, eh?

1747
02:11:12,048 --> 02:11:15,115
Five, four, three,

1748
02:11:15,117 --> 02:11:17,484
two, one. Now!

1749
02:11:48,918 --> 02:11:51,118
[♪♪♪]

1750
02:12:03,349 --> 02:12:05,916
[BULLETS RICOCHETING]

1751
02:12:32,545 --> 02:12:33,744
[FIRES]

1752
02:12:45,641 --> 02:12:46,924
[BULLET RICOCHETING]

1753
02:13:39,579 --> 02:13:40,560
[LAUGHS]

1754
02:13:44,617 --> 02:13:45,832
[CHUCKLING]

1755
02:15:02,528 --> 02:15:04,043
He's branched off.

1756
02:15:22,264 --> 02:15:25,615
[♪♪♪]

1757
02:15:29,238 --> 02:15:32,256
Never mind that.           
Go and get the brandy, huh?

1758
02:15:32,258 --> 02:15:33,924
Five-star Hennessy, of course.

1759
02:15:35,844 --> 02:15:39,079
[♪♪♪]

1760
02:15:39,081 --> 02:15:40,564
[CAR HORN HONKS]

1761
02:15:58,167 --> 02:15:59,166
[CHURCH BELLS CHIMING]

1762
02:15:59,168 --> 02:16:00,634
MAN:              
     Your Royal Highnesses,

1763
02:16:00,636 --> 02:16:04,771
my lords, ladies and gentlemen,

1764
02:16:04,773 --> 02:16:08,775
the toast is,          
   the bride and bridegroom:

1765
02:16:08,777 --> 02:16:12,412
Mr. and Mrs. James Bond.

1766
02:16:12,414 --> 02:16:14,714
CROWD [IN UNISON]:       
    Mr. and Mrs. James Bond.

1767
02:16:18,536 --> 02:16:20,837
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

1768
02:16:20,839 --> 02:16:22,156
WOMAN:             
       Good luck, Teresa.

1769
02:16:22,158 --> 02:16:23,690
Thank you.

1770
02:16:34,120 --> 02:16:37,203
[GIRLS SINGING INDISTINCTLY]

1771
02:16:38,874 --> 02:16:41,074
Anyway,             
       it's a pleasure...

1772
02:16:41,076 --> 02:16:44,678
to meet the man who cost me   
  three of my best operatives.

1773
02:16:44,680 --> 02:16:47,914
Yes, November '64,   
            the bullion job.    
      Mm.

1774
02:16:47,916 --> 02:16:49,583
You even got away    
           with quite a chunk

1775
02:16:49,585 --> 02:16:50,684
of the haul.

1776
02:16:50,686 --> 02:16:52,553
Tell me...

1777
02:16:52,555 --> 02:16:56,773
[GIRLS SINGING IN ITALIAN]

1778
02:16:57,976 --> 02:16:59,642
Congratulations, 007.

1779
02:16:59,644 --> 02:17:01,644
I must confess that             
I've sometimes thought you

1780
02:17:01,646 --> 02:17:03,280
a little, uh--                  
                  Irresponsible?

1781
02:17:03,282 --> 02:17:06,349
Exactly. That's exactly         
the word. Thank you.

1782
02:17:06,351 --> 02:17:08,785
This time, my boy,              
I can't complain.

1783
02:17:08,787 --> 02:17:10,404
Nor can I.

1784
02:17:10,406 --> 02:17:12,039
Excuse me.

1785
02:17:12,041 --> 02:17:13,106
Teresa?
                     Yes, Papa?

1786
02:17:13,108 --> 02:17:14,274
Look, James,

1787
02:17:14,276 --> 02:17:16,443
I know that we haven't          
always exactly seen--

1788
02:17:16,445 --> 02:17:17,710
Well, anyway,                   
don't forget,

1789
02:17:17,712 --> 02:17:19,546
if there's anything             
  you ever need--

1790
02:17:19,548 --> 02:17:21,748
Thank you, Q, but this time
        I've got the gadgets,

1791
02:17:21,750 --> 02:17:23,167
and I know how to use them.

1792
02:17:23,169 --> 02:17:25,369
<i> Au revoir.</i>

1793
02:17:25,371 --> 02:17:28,438
Remember, obey your husband     
      in all things.

1794
02:17:28,440 --> 02:17:31,241
You promise me? Huh?         
           But of course I will.

1795
02:17:31,243 --> 02:17:33,577
As I always obeyed you.

1796
02:17:34,346 --> 02:17:35,395
[CHUCKLES]

1797
02:17:36,097 --> 02:17:38,264
Of course.

1798
02:17:38,266 --> 02:17:39,599
Well, James,     
             I wish you luck.

1799
02:17:40,653 --> 02:17:42,452
For the first       
            and last time.

1800
02:17:42,454 --> 02:17:44,054
Remember?

1801
02:17:44,056 --> 02:17:45,421
An old proverb:

1802
02:17:45,423 --> 02:17:49,359
"Her price is far above rubies, 
or even your million pounds."

1803
02:17:49,361 --> 02:17:50,360
DRACO:                          
Teresa,

1804
02:17:50,362 --> 02:17:51,945
just because you are Mrs. Bond

1805
02:17:51,947 --> 02:17:53,163
don't forget my birthday

1806
02:17:53,165 --> 02:17:54,498
next year.            
Have I ever?

1807
02:17:54,500 --> 02:17:56,700
DRACO:     
               Both of you. Heh.
               Maybe all of you.

1808
02:17:56,702 --> 02:17:58,168
[CHUCKLES]

1809
02:17:59,137 --> 02:18:01,004
Come on, James.

1810
02:18:02,591 --> 02:18:05,843
Very happy.           
     Be happy, my darling.

1811
02:18:05,845 --> 02:18:07,077
Come on.

1812
02:18:08,514 --> 02:18:10,013
On your way.

1813
02:18:10,015 --> 02:18:11,014
<i> Au revoir.</i>

1814
02:18:11,016 --> 02:18:12,015
ALL:              
            Goodbye!

1815
02:18:12,017 --> 02:18:13,016
Drive carefully!

1816
02:18:13,018 --> 02:18:15,018
[HORN HONKING]

1817
02:18:25,130 --> 02:18:28,231
Miss Moneypenny,                
what would you do without me?

1818
02:18:28,233 --> 02:18:30,167
I always cry at weddings.

1819
02:18:30,169 --> 02:18:33,570
007 never had any respect
        for government property.

1820
02:18:33,572 --> 02:18:35,038
[HONKS HORN]

1821
02:18:38,210 --> 02:18:40,927
You know, I haven't given you
       a wedding present yet.

1822
02:18:40,929 --> 02:18:42,662
I had an idea about that.

1823
02:18:42,664 --> 02:18:45,231
Three girls, three boys.

1824
02:18:45,233 --> 02:18:46,766
Pleased?       
     Mmm.

1825
02:18:46,768 --> 02:18:48,051
Not bad for a start.

1826
02:18:49,805 --> 02:18:52,872
But, darling, now we have       
all the time in the world.

1827
02:18:53,842 --> 02:18:55,092
[SMOOCHES]

1828
02:18:55,094 --> 02:18:56,726
[CAR HORN HONKING        
          IN DISTANCE]

1829
02:18:57,896 --> 02:18:59,229
[INDISTINCT SHOUTING]

1830
02:18:59,231 --> 02:19:00,263
[LAUGHS]

1831
02:19:00,265 --> 02:19:02,599
[BOYS AND GIRLS
                   CHATTERING]

1832
02:19:03,485 --> 02:19:05,018
BOY:                    
Say it with flowers!

1833
02:19:05,020 --> 02:19:06,419
He's got a point.

1834
02:19:06,421 --> 02:19:08,922
We do look like an ad
             for a flower shop.

1835
02:19:08,924 --> 02:19:12,192
That reminds me,       
 I didn't even send you flowers.

1836
02:19:15,331 --> 02:19:19,333
Anyway, you have given me
           a wedding present.

1837
02:19:19,335 --> 02:19:21,368
The best I could have:

1838
02:19:21,370 --> 02:19:23,620
a future.

1839
02:19:23,622 --> 02:19:24,871
Mrs. Bond, shut...

1840
02:19:26,091 --> 02:19:27,090
up.

1841
02:19:27,092 --> 02:19:28,758
And don't eat it     
             all at once.

1842
02:19:30,896 --> 02:19:33,630
He loves me--                 
                  Instinctively.

1843
02:19:33,632 --> 02:19:35,299
Infuriatingly.

1844
02:19:35,301 --> 02:19:36,600
Intensely.

1845
02:19:36,602 --> 02:19:38,067
In...

1846
02:19:38,069 --> 02:19:39,052
In...?             
  In...

1847
02:19:39,054 --> 02:19:41,021
In...?   
       In...?

1848
02:19:41,023 --> 02:19:42,121
Indubitably.

1849
02:19:42,123 --> 02:19:44,641
[CHUCKLES]

1850
02:19:44,643 --> 02:19:46,709
First a boy,          
        and then a girl.

1851
02:19:55,904 --> 02:19:57,086
It's Blofeld!

1852
02:19:59,024 --> 02:20:00,023
It's Blofeld.

1853
02:20:25,984 --> 02:20:27,083
[ENGINE CUTS OFF]

1854
02:20:28,620 --> 02:20:31,187
It's all right.

1855
02:20:31,189 --> 02:20:34,558
It's quite all right, really.   
    She's having a rest.

1856
02:20:36,595 --> 02:20:38,662
We'll be going on soon.

1857
02:20:45,203 --> 02:20:46,570
There's no hurry, you see.

1858
02:20:46,572 --> 02:20:49,072
We have all the time            
   in the world.

1859
02:21:02,821 --> 02:21:04,755
[SOBBING QUIETLY]

1860
02:21:04,757 --> 02:21:08,825
[♪♪♪]

1861
02:21:19,571 --> 02:21:23,206
[♪♪♪]

